{"title_page": "Neela Vaanam", "text_new": "{{short description|1965 film by P. Madhavan}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Neela Vaanam\n| image          = Neela Vaanam.jpg\n| caption        = Poster\n| director       = [[P. Madhavan]]\n| producer       = Varadan\n| screenplay     = [[K. Balachander]]\n| starring       = [[Sivaji Ganesan]]<br />[[Devika]]<br />[[Rajasree]]\n| music          = [[M. S. Viswanathan]]\n| cinematography = [[M. Karnan]]\n| editing        = R. Devarajan\n| studio         = Pattu Films\n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|1965|12|10|df=y}}\n| country        = India\n| language       = Tamil\n}}\n\n'''''Neela Vaanam''''' ({{lit|Blue Sky}}) is a 1965 Indian [[Tamil language]] film, directed by [[P. Madhavan]] and produced by Varadan. The film stars [[Sivaji Ganesan]], [[Devika]], [[Rajasri]] and [[Nagesh]] in lead roles. The film had musical score by [[M. S. Viswanathan]].\n\n== Plot ==\nBabu ([[Sivaji Ganesan]]) and Vimala ([[Rajasree]]) are lovers. However, under a circumstance Babu is forced to marry the dying Gowri ([[Devika]]) without the acknowledgement of Vimala. Vimala and Gowri are friends. Shocked by her lover's marriage to Gowri, Vimala and Babu tried to keep their past as a secret from Gowri. What will happen to Gowri forms the rest of the story.\n\n== Cast ==\n*[[Sivaji Ganesan]] as Babu<ref name=\"Sport and Pastime\" />\n*[[Devika]] as Gowri<ref name=\"Sport and Pastime\" />\n*[[Rajasree]] as Vimala\n*[[S. V. Sahasranamam]] as Somanathan (Gowri's father)\n*[[V. K. Ramasamy (actor)|V. K. Ramasamy]] as Varatharajan (Vimala's father)\n*[[Nagesh]] as Prakash \n*Seethalakshmi\n*[[Kumari Padmini]] as Thilagam (Gowri's friend)\n*I. S. R\n*Harikrishnan as Sharma (contractor)\n*Comedy Shanmugam\n\n== Production ==\n''Neela Vaanam'' was directed by [[P. Madhavan]] and produced by Varadan under Pattu Films. The screenplay was written by [[K. Balachander]]. Cinematography was handled by Karnan, and the editing by R. Devarajan.<ref name=\"poster\" /> The final length of the film was {{convert|4800|metres|feet}}.<ref name=\"anandan\">{{Cite book |url=http://www.lakshmansruthi.com/cineprofiles/1965-cinedetails29.asp |title=Sadhanaigal Padaitha Thamizh Thiraipada Varalaru |last=Film News Anandan |date=23 October 2004 |publisher=Sivakami Publishers |location=Chennai |language=Tamil |trans-title=History of Landmark Tamil Films |author-link=Film News Anandan |archive-url=https://archive.is/1pL9Z |archive-date=5 October 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Soundtrack ==\nThe music was composed by [[M. S. Viswanathan]] and the lyrics were penned by [[Kannadasan]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tamilsongslyrics123.com/listlyrics/168 |title=Neelavanam songs |website=Tamilsongslyrics123 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190808074353/http://tamilsongslyrics123.com/listlyrics/168 |archive-date=2019-08-08 |access-date=2019-08-08}}</ref> [[Playback singer]]s are [[T. M. Soundararajan]], [[P. Susheela]] and [[L. R. Eswari]].<ref>{{Cite book |title=Thiraikalanjiyam&nbsp;\u2013 Part  2 |last=Neelamegam |first=G. |publisher=Manivasagar Publishers |edition=1st |location=Chennai |publication-date=November 2016 |page=208 |language=Tamil}}</ref>\n\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border&nbsp;\u2014 collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCF\" align=\"centre\"\n! No. !! Song !! Singer/s !! Lyrics !! Duration\n|-\n| 1 || ''O Lakshmi, O Sheela, O Maalaa'' || [[L. R. Eswari]] || rowspan=5|[[Kannadasan]] || 02:78\n|-\n| 2 || ''O Little Flower, See your lover'' || [[T. M. Soundararajan]] || 03:20\n|-\n| 3 || ''Oho Ho Odum Ennangale'' || [[P. Susheela]] || 03:41\n|-\n| 4 || ''Mangala Mangaiyum Maappillaiyum'' || [[P. Susheela]], [[L. R. Eswari]] || 04:10\n|-\n| 5 || ''Solladaa Vaay Thirandhu Ammaavenru'' || [[P. Susheela]] || 03:14\n|}\n\n== Reception ==\nNeela Vaanam was released on 10 December 1965.<ref name=\"poster\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.mayyam.com/talk/showthread.php?11868-%E0%AE%9A%E0%AE%BE%E0%AE%A4%E0%AE%A9%E0%AF%88-%E0%AE%9A%E0%AE%95%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%95%E0%AE%B0%E0%AE%B5%E0%AE%B0%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%A4%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%A4%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%AF%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%A9%E0%AF%8D-%E0%AE%A4%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%B0%E0%AF%88%E0%AE%AA%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%AA%E0%AE%9F-%E0%AE%9A%E0%AE%BE%E0%AE%A4%E0%AE%A9%E0%AF%88%E0%AE%95/page33 |title=Neela V\u0101nam |date=10 December 1965 |work=[[The Hindu]] |page=9}}</ref> T. M. Ramachandran of ''[[Sport and Pastime]]'' called it \"a poor film\" and criticised Madhavan's direction as \"naive\". He also noted \"There is nothing much to write home about K. Balachander's screenplay and dialogue\" but called Viswanathan's music \"pleasing\".<ref name=\"Sport and Pastime\">{{Cite magazine |last=Ramachandran |first=T. M. |date=8 January 1966 |title=Neela Vanam |url=https://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.20950/page/n109 |magazine=[[Sport and Pastime]] |volume=20 |page=51}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|1445694}}\n* {{YouTube|id=U3RAQvjyOhY|title=Neela Vanam}}\n{{P. Madhavan}}\n{{K. Balachander}}\n\n[[Category:1965 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:1960s Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by K. Balachander]]\n[[Category:Tamil films scored by M. S. Viswanathan]]\n[[Category:Films directed by P. Madhavan]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1965 film by P. Madhavan}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Neela Vaanam\n| image          = Neela Vaanam.jpg\n| caption        = Poster\n| director       = [[P. Madhavan]]\n| producer       = Varadan\n| screenplay     = [[K. Balachander]]\n| starring       = [[Sivaji Ganesan]]<br />[[Devika]]<br />[[Rajasree]]\n| music          = [[M. S. Viswanathan]]\n| cinematography = [[M. Karnan]]\n| editing        = R. Devarajan\n| studio         = Pattu Films\n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|1965|12|10|df=y}}\n| country        = India\n| language       = Tamil\n}}\n\n'''''Neela Vaanam''''' ({{lit|Blue Sky}}) is a 1965 Indian [[Tamil language]] film, directed by [[P. Madhavan]] and produced by Varadan. The film stars [[Sivaji Ganesan]], [[Devika]], [[Rajasri]] and [[Nagesh]] in lead roles. The film had musical score by [[M. S. Viswanathan]].\n\n== Plot ==\nBabu ([[Sivaji Ganesan]]) and Vimala ([[Rajasree]]) are lovers. However, under a circumstance Babu is forced to get married with dying Gowri ([[Devika]]) without the acknowledgement of Vimala. Vimala and Gowri are friends. Shocked by the fact her lover get married to Gowri, Vimala and Babu tried to keep their past as a secret from Gowri. What will happen to Gowri forms the rest of the story.\n\n== Cast ==\n*[[Sivaji Ganesan]] as Babu<ref name=\"Sport and Pastime\" />\n*[[Devika]] as Gowri<ref name=\"Sport and Pastime\" />\n*[[Rajasree]] as Vimala\n*[[S. V. Sahasranamam]] as Somanathan (Gowri Father)\n*[[V. K. Ramasamy (actor)|V. K. Ramasamy]] as Varatharajan (Vimala Father)\n*[[Nagesh]] as Prakash \n*Seethalakshmi\n*[[Kumari Padmini]] as Thilagam (Gowri Friend)\n*I. S. R\n*Harikrishnan as Sharma (Contrector)\n*Comedy Shanmugam\n\n== Production ==\n''Neela Vaanam'' was directed by [[P. Madhavan]] and produced by Varadan under Pattu Films. The screenplay was written by [[K. Balachander]]. Cinematography was handled by Karnan, and the editing by R. Devarajan.<ref name=\"poster\" /> The final length of the film was {{convert|4800|metres|feet}}.<ref name=\"anandan\">{{Cite book |url=http://www.lakshmansruthi.com/cineprofiles/1965-cinedetails29.asp |title=Sadhanaigal Padaitha Thamizh Thiraipada Varalaru |last=Film News Anandan |date=23 October 2004 |publisher=Sivakami Publishers |location=Chennai |language=Tamil |trans-title=History of Landmark Tamil Films |author-link=Film News Anandan |archive-url=https://archive.is/1pL9Z |archive-date=5 October 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Soundtrack ==\nThe music was composed by [[M. S. Viswanathan]] and the lyrics were penned by [[Kannadasan]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tamilsongslyrics123.com/listlyrics/168 |title=Neelavanam songs |website=Tamilsongslyrics123 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190808074353/http://tamilsongslyrics123.com/listlyrics/168 |archive-date=2019-08-08 |access-date=2019-08-08}}</ref> [[Playback singer]]s are [[T. M. Soundararajan]], [[P. Susheela]] and [[L. R. Eswari]].<ref>{{Cite book |title=Thiraikalanjiyam&nbsp;\u2013 Part  2 |last=Neelamegam |first=G. |publisher=Manivasagar Publishers |edition=1st |location=Chennai |publication-date=November 2016 |page=208 |language=Tamil}}</ref>\n\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border&nbsp;\u2014 collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCF\" align=\"centre\"\n! No. !! Song !! Singer/s !! Lyrics !! Duration\n|-\n| 1 || ''O Lakshmi, O Sheela, O Maalaa'' || [[L. R. Eswari]] || rowspan=5|[[Kannadasan]] || 02:78\n|-\n| 2 || ''O Little Flower, See your lover'' || [[T. M. Soundararajan]] || 03:20\n|-\n| 3 || ''Oho Ho Odum Ennangale'' || [[P. Susheela]] || 03:41\n|-\n| 4 || ''Mangala Mangaiyum Maappillaiyum'' || [[P. Susheela]], [[L. R. Eswari]] || 04:10\n|-\n| 5 || ''Solladaa Vaay Thirandhu Ammaavenru'' || [[P. Susheela]] || 03:14\n|}\n\n== Reception ==\nNeela Vaanam was released on 10 December 1965.<ref name=\"poster\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.mayyam.com/talk/showthread.php?11868-%E0%AE%9A%E0%AE%BE%E0%AE%A4%E0%AE%A9%E0%AF%88-%E0%AE%9A%E0%AE%95%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%95%E0%AE%B0%E0%AE%B5%E0%AE%B0%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%A4%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%A4%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%AF%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%A9%E0%AF%8D-%E0%AE%A4%E0%AE%BF%E0%AE%B0%E0%AF%88%E0%AE%AA%E0%AF%8D%E0%AE%AA%E0%AE%9F-%E0%AE%9A%E0%AE%BE%E0%AE%A4%E0%AE%A9%E0%AF%88%E0%AE%95/page33 |title=Neela V\u0101nam |date=10 December 1965 |work=[[The Hindu]] |page=9}}</ref> T. M. Ramachandran of ''[[Sport and Pastime]]'' called it \"a poor film\" and criticised Madhavan's direction as \"naive\". He also noted \"There is nothing much to write home about K. Balachander's screenplay and dialogue\" but called Viswanathan's music \"pleasing\".<ref name=\"Sport and Pastime\">{{Cite magazine |last=Ramachandran |first=T. M. |date=8 January 1966 |title=Neela Vanam |url=https://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.20950/page/n109 |magazine=[[Sport and Pastime]] |volume=20 |page=51}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|1445694}}\n* {{YouTube|id=U3RAQvjyOhY|title=Neela Vanam}}\n{{P. Madhavan}}\n{{K. Balachander}}\n\n[[Category:1965 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:1960s Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by K. Balachander]]\n[[Category:Tamil films scored by M. S. Viswanathan]]\n[[Category:Films directed by P. Madhavan]]\n", "name_user": "Jellysandwich0", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neela_Vaanam"}
{"title_page": "Hot Fudge", "text_new": "{{about|the American children's television series|the Robbie Williams song|Escapology (album)}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name = The Hot Fudge Show\n| show_name_2 = '''''Hot Fudge'''''<br>'''''The Hot Fudge Show'''''\n| genre = [[Children's television series]]\n| starring = [[Arte Johnson]] (season 1)<br>[[Larry Santos]]<br>[[Ron Coden]]<br>Amanda Caruthers<br>Yolanda Williams\n| voices = Bob Elnicky<br>Larry Santos<br>Ron Coden\n| country = United States\n| num_seasons = 4\n| producer = Barry Hurd<br>Bob Elnicky\n| runtime = 22&ndash;24 minutes\n| network = [[WXYZ-TV]]<br>[[television syndication|Syndication]]\n| first_aired = September 1976\n| last_aired  = 1980\n}}\n\n'''''Hot Fudge''''' (also known as '''''The Hot Fudge Show''''') is an [[United States|American]] [[children's television series]] that was produced in [[Detroit, Michigan|Detroit]] by [[WXYZ-TV]] ([[Owned-and-operated station|owned and operated]] at the time by [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]) and distributed by the [[Lexington Broadcast Services Company]].<ref name=toonarific>[http://www.toonarific.com/show.php?show_id=4535 Hot Fudge Show, The @ Toonarific Cartoons<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Originally airing only in Detroit beginning in [[1974 in television|1974]], the show grew in popularity and was [[television syndication|syndicated]] nationally from [[1976 in television|1976]] to [[1980 in television|1980]]; a few of WXYZ's sister [[Disney\u2013ABC Television Group|ABC-owned stations]] (including [[KGO-TV|KGO]] and [[WLS-TV|WLS]]) carried the program.\n\n==Overview==\nFeaturing music, songs, and sketches with live [[actor]]s and [[puppet]]s (known as the \"Mits\"), the show was originally hosted by [[Arte Johnson]]. The duo of the bearded musician '''Larry''' ([[Larry Santos]]) and green fuzzy puppet '''Seymour''' (voiced by producer Bob Elnicky) took over after the first season.\n\nGlenn Denver, a puppet parody of [[John Denver]], released an album titled ''Glenn Denver Sings Country Songs from the Hot Fudge T.V. Show''. Three other ''Hot Fudge'' albums were released; The Electric Fuzz's ''Rock 'N Roll from the Hot Fudge T.V. Show'', ''Larry and Seymour Sing Songs from the Hot Fudge T.V. Show'', and ''Hooray For Friendship and 9 Other Hits from the Hot Fudge T.V. Show, Plus Nine More''. All of the albums have been released on CD.\n\nA ''Hot Fudge'' episode was submitted to the [[University of Georgia]] for a [[Peabody Award]] in 1974; though not selected for the award itself, it was retained for the university's Peabody Awards Collection Archives.<ref>[http://dbs.galib.uga.edu/cgi-bin/ultimate.cgi?dbs=parc&userid=galileo&action=search&_cc=1 Peabody Awards Collection Archives Record]</ref> The show won a Puppeteers of America ACT AWARD in 1976.<ref>[http://www.puppetconnection.com/credentials.html Marilyn O'Connor Miller - Credentials, Awards, Honors, and Affiliations<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Sketches and characters==\n* '''Holy Moley!''':  A sketch where a simple-minded man (Ron Coden) tries to outwit problems, but gets socked back.\n* '''Name That Feeling''': Professor Emotion (Ron Coden) hosts a parody of ''[[Name That Tune]]'' with puppet contestants watching a video clip of other puppets and trying to guess how they feel.   This is shown in two parts with an in-show commercial sandwiched in-between.\n* '''Write On!''': A segment where many of the puppet characters read jokes or riddles sent in by kids.\n*'''Newsreel''': Similar to the \"Picture Picture\" segments of \"[[Mr. Rogers Neighborhood]], film footage of various items such as paper being produced would be narrated by various kids in the style of a newsreel.\n*'''Unreasonable Report''': News sketches featuring Harry Unreasonable, a parody of news anchor [[Harry Reasoner]].\n* '''Hot Fudge Gang'''/'''The Mits'''/'''Happening!''': Various sketches featuring children and adults.\n* '''Detective Tomato''' (Ron Coden) giving advice to children than leaving through the door behind him, only to have something happen to him when he goes through.\n* '''Elton Seymour''': Seymour playing a tune in the guise of [[Elton John]], usually featured at the beginning of the show.\n* '''Mr. Nasty''' (Ron Coden), who loves being booed by his audience, gives tips on how to be as nasty as him...only to have the tables turned on him by his landlady in the end, prompting the audience to applaud. \n* '''Amanda Caruthers''' (later replaced by '''Yolanda Williams''') portraying various characters in sketches, often giving kindly advice to the inquiring puppets.\n\n==2007 reunion special==\nOn Wednesday December 5, 2007, Detroit [[PBS]] member station [[WTVS]] presented a 90-minute reunion special, featuring the original cast, including Larry and Seymour. The special featured memories of the program interspersed with clips from the series. <ref>Info from the TV listings at http://www.wtvs.org/</ref> A [[rerun]] of the episode was aired on December 14, 2007.\n\n==Discography==\n*''Music From The Hot Fudge Show'' - single on S.H.Y. Records (1974)\n*''Hooray For Friendship And 9 Other Hits From The Hot Fudge T.V. Show'' (1996)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{imdb title|id=0287228}}\n* {{tv.com show|the-hot-fudge}} \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20161022133229/http://www.hotfudgeshow.com/ Hot Fudge Show.com] {{dead link}}\n* [http://www.toonarific.com/show.php?show_id=4535 ''The Hot Fudge Show'' at Toonarific.com]\n* [http://www.fuzzymemories.tv/screen.php?c=453&m=hot%20fudge%20show&p=1 Hot Fudge Show (Excerpt & Bumper), Courtesy of www.FuzzyMemories.TV - The Museum of Classic Chicago Television.]\n\n[[Category:1976 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1980 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:1970s American children's comedy television series]]\n[[Category:1980s American children's comedy television series]]\n[[Category:1970s American sketch comedy television series]]\n[[Category:1980s American sketch comedy television series]]\n[[Category:1970s American variety television series]]\n[[Category:1980s American variety television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:First-run syndicated television programs in the United States]]\n[[Category:American television programs featuring puppetry]]\n[[Category:Television series by Fremantle (company)]]\n[[Category:Children's sketch comedy]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the American children's television series|the Robbie Williams song|Escapology (album)}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name = The Hot Fudge Show\n| show_name_2 = '''''Hot Fudge'''''<br>'''''The Hot Fudge Show'''''\n| genre = [[Children's television series]]\n| starring = [[Arte Johnson]] (season 1)<br>[[Larry Santos]]<br>[[Ron Coden]]<br>Amanda Caruthers<br>Yolanda Williams\n| voices = Bob Elnicky<br>Larry Santos<br>Ron Coden\n| country = United States\n| num_seasons = 4\n| producer = Barry Hurd<br>Bob Elnicky\n| runtime = 22&ndash;24 minutes\n| network = [[WXYZ-TV]]<br>[[television syndication|Syndication]]\n| first_aired = September 1976\n| last_aired  = 1980\n}}\n\n'''''Hot Fudge''''' (also known as '''''The Hot Fudge Show''''') is an [[United States|American]] [[children's television series]] that was produced in [[Detroit, Michigan|Detroit]] by [[WXYZ-TV]] ([[Owned-and-operated station|owned and operated]] at the time by [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]) and distributed by the [[Lexington Broadcast Services Company]].<ref name=toonarific>[http://www.toonarific.com/show.php?show_id=4535 Hot Fudge Show, The @ Toonarific Cartoons<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Originally airing only in Detroit beginning in [[1974 in television|1974]], the show grew in popularity and was [[television syndication|syndicated]] nationally from [[1976 in television|1976]] to [[1980 in television|1980]]; a few of WXYZ's sister [[Disney\u2013ABC Television Group|ABC-owned stations]] (including [[KGO-TV|KGO]] and [[WLS-TV|WLS]]) carried the program.\n\n==Overview==\nFeaturing music, songs, and sketches with live [[actor]]s and [[puppet]]s (known as the \"Mits\"), the show was originally hosted by [[Arte Johnson]]. The duo of the bearded musician '''Larry''' ([[Larry Santos]]) and green fuzzy puppet '''Seymour''' (voiced by producer Bob Elnicky) took over after the first season.\n\nGlenn Denver, a puppet parody of [[John Denver]], released an album titled ''Glenn Denver Sings Country Songs from the Hot Fudge T.V. Show''. Three other ''Hot Fudge'' albums were released; The Electric Fuzz's ''Rock 'N Roll from the Hot Fudge T.V. Show'', ''Larry and Seymour Sing Songs from the Hot Fudge T.V. Show'', and ''Hooray For Friendship and 9 Other Hits from the Hot Fudge T.V. Show, Plus Nine More''. All of the albums have been released on CD.\n\nA ''Hot Fudge'' episode was submitted to the [[University of Georgia]] for a [[Peabody Award]] in 1974; though not selected for the award itself, it was retained for the university's Peabody Awards Collection Archives.<ref>[http://dbs.galib.uga.edu/cgi-bin/ultimate.cgi?dbs=parc&userid=galileo&action=search&_cc=1 Peabody Awards Collection Archives Record]</ref> The show won a Puppeteers of America ACT AWARD in 1976.<ref>[http://www.puppetconnection.com/credentials.html Marilyn O'Connor Miller - Credentials, Awards, Honors, and Affiliations<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Sketches and characters==\n* '''Holy Moley!''':  A sketch where a simple-minded man (Ron Coden) tries to outwit problems, but gets socked back.\n* '''Name That Feeling''': Professor Emotion (Ron Coden) hosts a parody of ''[[Name That Tune]]'' with puppet contestants watching a video clip of other puppets and trying to guess how they feel.   This is shown in two parts with an in-show commercial sandwiched in-between.\n* '''Write On!''': A segment where many of the puppet characters read jokes or riddles sent in by kids.\n*'''Newsreel''': Similar to the \"Picture Picture\" segments of \"[[Mr. Rogers Neighborhood]], film footage of various items such as paper being produced would be narrated by various kids in the style of a newsreel.\n*'''Unreasonable Report''': News sketches featuring Harry Unreasonable, a parody of news anchor [[Harry Reasoner]].\n* '''Hot Fudge Gang'''/'''The Mits'''/'''Happening!''': Various sketches featuring children and adults.\n* '''Detective Tomato''' (Ron Coden) giving advice to children than leaving through the door behind him, only to have something happen to him when he goes through.\n* '''Elton Seymour''': Seymour playing a tune in the guise of [[Elton John]], usually featured at the beginning of the show.\n* '''Mr. Nasty''' (Ron Coden), who loves being booed by his audience, gives tips on how to be as nasty as him...only to have the tables turned on him by his landlady in the end, prompting the audience to applaud. \n* '''Amanda Caruthers''' (later replaced by '''Yolanda Williams''') portraying various characters in sketches, often giving kindly advice to the inquiring puppets.\n\n==2007 reunion special==\nOn Wednesday December 5, 2007, Detroit [[PBS]] member station [[WTVS]] presented a 90-minute reunion special, featuring the original cast, including Larry and Seymour. The special featured memories of the program interspersed with clips from the series. <ref>Info from the TV listings at http://www.wtvs.org/</ref> A [[rerun]] of the episode was aired on December 14, 2007.\n\n==Discography==\n*''Music From The Hot Fudge Show'' - single on S.H.Y. Records (1974)\n*''Hooray For Friendship And 9 Other Hits From The Hot Fudge T.V. Show'' (1996)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{imdb title|id=0287228}}\n* {{tv.com show|the-hot-fudge}} {{dead link}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20161022133229/http://www.hotfudgeshow.com/ Hot Fudge Show.com]\n* [http://www.toonarific.com/show.php?show_id=4535 ''The Hot Fudge Show'' at Toonarific.com]\n* [http://www.fuzzymemories.tv/screen.php?c=453&m=hot%20fudge%20show&p=1 Hot Fudge Show (Excerpt & Bumper), Courtesy of www.FuzzyMemories.TV - The Museum of Classic Chicago Television.]\n\n[[Category:1976 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1980 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:1970s American children's comedy television series]]\n[[Category:1980s American children's comedy television series]]\n[[Category:1970s American sketch comedy television series]]\n[[Category:1980s American sketch comedy television series]]\n[[Category:1970s American variety television series]]\n[[Category:1980s American variety television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:First-run syndicated television programs in the United States]]\n[[Category:American television programs featuring puppetry]]\n[[Category:Television series by Fremantle (company)]]\n[[Category:Children's sketch comedy]]\n", "name_user": "Ty78ejui", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixed mistake dead link is for the Hot Fudge. com website which was never even developed as a site", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hot_Fudge"}
{"title_page": "2007 Labour Party leadership election (UK)", "text_new": "{{for timeline|Timeline of the 2007 Labour Party leadership election (UK){{!}}Timeline of the 2007 Labour Party leadership election}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name      = 2007 Labour Party leadership election\n| country            = \n| flag_image = \n| type               = presidential\n| ongoing            = no\n| previous_election  = 1994 Labour Party leadership election\n| previous_year      = 1994\n| next_election      = 2010 Labour Party leadership election (UK)\n| next_year          = 2010\n| 1blank             = Nominations\n| 2blank             = Percentage\n| 3blank             = Popular&nbsp;vote\n| election_date      = {{Start and end dates|2007|5|10|2007|6|24|df=yes}}\n\n| image1             = Gordon Brown official.jpg\n| image1_size        = 170x170px\n| candidate1         = [[Gordon Brown]]\n| colour1            =  DC241F\n| 1data1             = \n| 2data1             = \n| 3data1             = ''Unopposed''\n| title              = Leader\n| before_election    = [[Tony Blair]]\n| after_election     = [[Gordon Brown]]\n}}\nThe '''2007 Labour Party leadership election''' was formally triggered on 10 May 2007 by the resignation of [[Tony Blair]], [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[Labour Party (UK)#Leaders of the Labour Party since 1906|Leader]] since [[1994 Labour Party leadership election|the previous leadership contest]] on 21 July 1994. At the same time that Blair resigned, [[John Prescott]] resigned as [[Labour Party (UK)#Deputy Leaders of the Labour Party since 1922|Deputy Leader]], triggering [[2007 Labour Party deputy leadership election|a concurrent election for the deputy leadership]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/5386428.stm |title=Prescott tells Labour: I'm sorry |author= |date=2006-09-28 |work=[[BBC News]] |publisher= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6642805.stm |title=Prescott quits as Deputy Leader |date=2007-05-10 |work=[[BBC News Online]]}}</ref>\n\nInformal campaigning had been ongoing ever since Blair announced in 2004 that he would not be fighting a fourth general election as leader. Pressure for a timetable eventually led him to announce on 7 September 2006 that he would step down within a year.<ref>{{cite news |title=I will quit within a year \u2014 Blair |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/5322094.stm |work=BBC News Online |date=2006-09-07 |accessdate=2006-11-18}}</ref> Labour's [[National Executive Committee]] (NEC) met on 13 May 2007 to decide a timetable.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/6457597.stm |title=Labour leader election timetable |author= |date=2007-03-21 |format= |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/6639945.stm |title=Blair will stand down on 27 June |date=2007-05-10 |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref> Nominations opened on 14 May and closed at 12:30 UTC+1 on 17 May 2007.\n\nBlair said he expected [[Gordon Brown]] to succeed him, and that Brown \"would make an excellent Prime Minister\". When nominations for the leadership elections opened, Blair was one of those nominating Brown.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.labour.org.uk/leadership/gordon_brown123 |title=Labour leadership contest - Gordon Brown nominators |work=[[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070517084437/http://www.labour.org.uk/leadership/gordon_brown123 |archivedate=2007-05-17 }}</ref> From the start, most observers considered Brown the overwhelming favourite to succeed Blair; [[John McDonnell]], his only challenger, failed to secure enough nominations in order to get onto the ballot, and conceded defeat.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/6234692.stm |title=Harman wins deputy leader contest |date=24 June 2007 |work=BBC News Online}}</ref> Brown received 313 (88.2%) nominations to McDonnell's 29 (8.2%), making it mathematically impossible for anyone other than Brown to be nominated.\n\nThe election process concluded with Brown being declared leader at a special conference on 24 June 2007. On 27 June, Blair resigned as [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] and was succeeded by Brown.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/output/Page4692.asp |title=Queen and Government |work=Website of the [[Monarchy of the United Kingdom|British Monarchy]]}}</ref>\n\nIf Brown had been opposed, Labour Party members would for the first time have directly elected a new Prime Minister.\n\n==Candidates==\n[[John McDonnell]] and [[Gordon Brown]] were the only candidates as the election process began with the nominations round. In order to secure a place on the ballot paper, candidates needed to submit their nominations to the [[National Executive Committee]] (NEC) by 17 May, each supported by at least 12.5% of [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] MPs (45 Labour MPs, including the candidate themselves). Brown, the only successfully nominated candidate, was declared leader at a special Labour conference on 24 June 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.labour.org.uk/leadership/nominations_close_-_1230_thursday_17_may |title=Labour leadership, close of nominations |date=2007-05-17 |work=Labour Party |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070921050327/http://www.labour.org.uk/leadership/nominations_close_-_1230_thursday_17_may |archivedate=2007-09-21 }}</ref>\n\n* Gordon Brown, [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/5376760.stm |title=Brown sets out leadership vision |author= |date=2006-09-26 |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref> long the favourite candidate to succeed [[Tony Blair]], received 313 nominations and was successfully nominated.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/6664063.stm |title= Brown 'humbled' by Labour backing |date=2007-05-17 |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref>\n* John McDonnell, chair of the [[Socialist Campaign Group]], pledged to merge Old Labour and New Labour into what he calls Real Labour, and to \"save the Labour government from itself\". He was hoping to get the backing of all those who had been backing [[Michael Meacher]], but did not do so;<ref>{{cite news |url=http://politics.guardian.co.uk/labourleadership/story/0,,2081121,00.html |title=Brown trying to prevent contest, claims McDonnell |date=2007-05-16 |work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher= |location=London |first=H\u00e9l\u00e8ne |last=Mulholland |accessdate=2010-05-07}}</ref> with 29 nominations, he was 16 short of the minimum required number, and was not successfully nominated.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/5179556.stm |title=Labour MP launches leadership bid |author= |date=2006-07-14 |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tni.org/detail_page.phtml?act_id=16809 |title=Challenging Brown from the Left? Meacher and McDonnell interviewed |author=Oscar Reyes |authorlink=Oscar Reyes |date=2007-05-11 |work=[[Red Pepper (magazine)|Red Pepper]] |publisher=[[Transnational Institute]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/UKNews1/idUKL1464496220070515 |title=McDonnell short for leadership race |author= |date=2007-05-15 |work=[[Reuters]] |publisher= }}</ref>\n* Michael Meacher (withdrew on 14 May 2007), former [[Secretary of State for the Environment, Transport and the Regions|Minister of State for the Environment]], was a candidate but withdrew after failing to get enough nominations. On 27 April 2007, he and McDonnell announced that whichever of them had the support of fewer Labour MPs at the point of Tony Blair's resignation would withdraw from the campaign and support the other.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6598683.stm |title=Left rivals unite to target Brown |author= |date=2007-04-27 |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref> On 10 May, they delayed their announcement because \"levels of support for each were too close to call\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/6642331.stm |title=Brown rivals delay bid decision |date=2007-05-10 |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref> Meacher gave his support to McDonnell on 14 May, but not all his supporters switched allegiance.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6652651.stm |title=Brown 'faces McDonnell challenge' |author= |date=2007-05-14 |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref>\n\n==Nominations and result==\n\n{| class =\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! colspan=2|Candidate !! Constituency !! Nominations !! Share !! Nominated?\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}};\"| || [[Gordon Brown]] || [[Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath (UK Parliament constituency)|Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath]] || 313 || 88.2% || {{Yes}}\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}};\"| || [[John McDonnell]] ||[[Hayes and Harlington (UK Parliament constituency)|Hayes and Harlington]]|| 29 || 8.2% || {{No}}\n|-\n|}\n\nOnly Gordon Brown attained over 45 nominations and was thus elected unopposed.\n\n==Suggested candidates who declined to run==\nDuring the months leading up to Tony Blair's resignation, media attention focused on a wide range of Labour politicians, most of whom publicly refused to stand:\n*[[Hilary Benn]], the [[Secretary of State for International Development]], was touted as a possible candidate to succeed Blair. However, he backed Gordon Brown.\n*[[Charles Clarke]], former [[Home Secretary]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.eveningnews24.co.uk/content/news/story.aspx?brand=ENOnline&category=News&tBrand=ENOnline&tCategory=news&itemid=NOED15%20Jan%202007%2013%3A04%3A56%3A433 |title=City MP says he won't fight Brown |date=2007-01-15 |work=[[Norwich Evening News]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928000707/http://www.eveningnews24.co.uk/content/news/story.aspx?brand=ENOnline&category=News&tBrand=ENOnline&tCategory=news&itemid=NOED15%20Jan%202007%2013%3A04%3A56%3A433 |archivedate=2007-09-28 }}</ref> had insisted he would stand if [[David Miliband]] did not, but later softened his position with praise for Brown, also saying that the Labour Party didn't have the appetite for a contest. He indicated that he would like to serve in a future Labour Cabinet;<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article1596687.ece |title=Clarke ready to run for leader |author=David Cracknell |author2=Isabel Oakeshott |date=2007-04-01 |work=[[The Sunday Times (UK)|Sunday Times]] |publisher= |location=London|author2-link=Isabel Oakeshott }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.politics.co.uk/news/features/labour-leadership/clarke-rules-out-leadership-with-praise-brown-$472810.htm |title=Clarke rules out leadership with praise for Brown |author= |date=2007-05-03 |publisher= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/6627153.stm |title=Clarke 'will not challenge Brown' |author= |date=2007-05-04 |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref> however, he was not offered any position, and went on to lose his seat in the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|subsequent general election in 2010]].\n*[[John Hutton (Labour MP)|John Hutton]], [[Secretary of State for Work and Pensions]], had said there should be a serious opponent to Brown, but on 6 May 2007 declared his support for Brown.<ref name=\"Will Blair and Brown get their way?\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/5319148.stm |title=Will Blair and Brown get their way? |author= |date=2006-09-06 |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref><ref name=\"Reid gives Brown clear run to No 10\">{{cite news |url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/reid-gives-brown-clear-run-to-no-10-1-1418911 |title=Reid gives Brown clear run to No 10 |author= |date=2007-05-06 |work=[[Scotland on Sunday]] |publisher= |accessdate=2019-05-19}}</ref>\n*[[Glenda Jackson]], MP for [[Hampstead and Highgate]] and former transport minister, had repeatedly threatened to stand as a stalking horse candidate against Blair from 2005 onwards; however, she backed Brown for the leadership.\n*[[Alan Johnson]], [[Secretary of State for Education]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6133276.stm |title=Johnson backing Brown for leader |author= |date=2006-11-09 |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref> In autumn 2006, he was (alongside [[John Reid, Baron Reid of Cardowan|John Reid]]) being touted as one of very few serious contenders, but later backed Brown.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/5341812.stm |title=Johnson fuels leadership speculation |author= |date=2006-09-26 |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref>\n*[[Lynne Jones]], MP for [[Birmingham Selly Oak (UK Parliament constituency)|Birmingham Selly Oak]], said that she would stand against Brown for the leadership as a leftwing candidate. However, she later backed [[John McDonnell]].\n*[[Alan Milburn]] ruled out standing for the Labour leadership on 11 May 2007, but previously had refused to rule it out.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/5237874.stm |title=Labour leadership contenders |author= |date=2007-05-10 |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://politics.guardian.co.uk/labourleadership/story/0,,2077454,00.html |title=Blair backs Brown as chancellor launches campaign |author=Deborah Summers and agencies |date=2007-05-11 |work=The Guardian |publisher= |location=London}}</ref>\n*[[David Miliband]], [[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]]. Speculation that he would be persuaded to stand was intense during spring 2007, including suggestions that Blair saw him as a possible successor.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2007/03/27/nlabour27.xml |title=Labour slump may spark Miliband challenge |author= |date=2007-03-28 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |publisher= |location=London |accessdate=2010-05-07}}</ref> However, Miliband declined to stand, saying publicly that this had been his unwavering position for three years, and that he would vote for Brown.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6513013.stm |title=Beckett warns Miliband not to run |author= |date=2007-03-31 |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://politics.guardian.co.uk/labourleadership/story/0,,2054433,00.html |title=Miliband: I will not be seduced into leadership bid |author= |date=2007-04-11 |work=The Guardian |publisher= |location=London |first=Matthew |last=Tempest |accessdate=2010-05-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/6563747.stm |title=Miliband 'won't run for leader' |author= |date=2007-04-17 |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref>\n*[[John Reid]], [[Home Secretary]], had said he would not reveal whether he would stand or not until there was a vacancy, but on 6 May announced he would be voting for Brown and had decided to leave the Cabinet along with Blair.<ref name=\"Will Blair and Brown get their way?\"/><ref name=\"Reid gives Brown clear run to No 10\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/5377710.stm |title=Reid's end-of-rally job pitch |author= |date=2006-09-28 |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/6629877.stm |title=Reid to quit as home secretary |date=2007-05-06 |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref>\n*[[Jack Straw]], [[Leader of the House of Commons]], announced on 25 March that he would be running Gordon Brown's leadership campaign.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6492417.stm |title=Straw to run Brown leadership bid |author= |date=2007-03-25 |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref> He was appointed [[Lord Chancellor]] and [[Secretary of State for Justice]] in Brown's first cabinet.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/6247502.stm |title=Brown unveils huge Cabinet revamp |date=2007-06-28 |work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[2007 Labour Party deputy leadership election]]\n*[[2010 United Kingdom general election]]\n*[[Blair\u2013Brown deal]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.labour.org.uk/ Labour Party website]\n*{{citation |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/in_depth/uk_politics/2006/blair_succession/default.stm |title=Blair succession |publisher=BBC News |type=Special Report}}\n\n{{UK Labour Party}}\n{{Labour Party leadership election, 2007|state=expanded}}\n{{Gordon Brown}}\n\n[[Category:2007 elections in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) leadership elections|2007]]\n[[Category:Single-candidate elections]]\n", "text_old": "{{for timeline|Timeline of the 2007 Labour Party leadership election (UK){{!}}Timeline of the 2007 Labour Party leadership election}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name      = 2007 Labour Party leadership election\n| country            = \n| flag_image = \n| type               = presidential\n| ongoing            = no\n| previous_election  = 1994 Labour Party leadership election\n| previous_year      = 1994\n| next_election      = 2010 Labour Party leadership election (UK)\n| next_year          = 2010\n| 1blank             = Nominations\n| 2blank             = Percentage\n| 3blank             = Popular&nbsp;vote\n| election_date      = {{Start and end dates|2007|5|10|2007|6|24|df=yes}}\n\n| image1             = Gordon Brown official.jpg\n| image1_size        = 170x170px\n| candidate1         = [[Gordon Brown]]\n| colour1            =  DC241F\n| 1data1             = \n| 2data1             = \n| 3data1             = ''Unopposed''\n| title              = Leader\n| before_election    = [[Tony Blair]]\n| after_election     = [[Gordon Brown]]\n}}\nThe '''2007 Labour Party leadership election''' was formally triggered on 10 May 2007 by the resignation of [[Tony Blair]], [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[Labour Party (UK)#Leaders of the Labour Party since 1906|Leader]] since [[1994 Labour Party leadership election|the previous leadership contest]] on 21 July 1994. At the same time that Blair resigned, [[John Prescott]] resigned as [[Labour Party (UK)#Deputy Leaders of the Labour Party since 1922|Deputy Leader]], triggering [[2007 Labour Party deputy leadership election|a concurrent election for the deputy leadership]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/5386428.stm |title=Prescott tells Labour: I'm sorry |author= |date=2006-09-28 |work=[[BBC News]] |publisher= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6642805.stm |title=Prescott quits as Deputy Leader |date=2007-05-10 |work=[[BBC News Online]]}}</ref>\n\nInformal campaigning had been ongoing ever since Blair announced in 2004 that he would not be fighting a fourth general election as leader. Pressure for a timetable eventually led him to announce on 7 September 2006 that he would step down within a year.<ref>{{cite news |title=I will quit within a year \u2014 Blair |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/5322094.stm |work=BBC News Online |date=2006-09-07 |accessdate=2006-11-18}}</ref> Labour's [[National Executive Committee]] (NEC) met on 13 May 2007 to decide a timetable.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/6457597.stm |title=Labour leader election timetable |author= |date=2007-03-21 |format= |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/6639945.stm |title=Blair will stand down on 27 June |date=2007-05-10 |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref> Nominations opened on 14 May and closed at 12:30 UTC+1 on 17 May 2007.\n\nBlair said he expected [[Gordon Brown]] to succeed him, and that Brown \"would make an excellent Prime Minister\". When nominations for the leadership elections opened, Blair was one of those nominating Brown.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.labour.org.uk/leadership/gordon_brown123 |title=Labour leadership contest - Gordon Brown nominators |work=[[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070517084437/http://www.labour.org.uk/leadership/gordon_brown123 |archivedate=2007-05-17 }}</ref> From the start, most observers considered Brown the overwhelming favourite to succeed Blair; [[John McDonnell]], his only challenger, failed to secure enough nominations in order to get onto the ballot, and conceded defeat.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/6234692.stm |title=Harman wins deputy leader contest |date=24 June 2007 |work=BBC News Online}}</ref> Brown received 313 (88.2%) nominations to McDonnell's 29 (8.2%), making it mathematically impossible for anyone other than Brown to be nominated.\n\nThe election process concluded with Brown being declared leader at a special conference on 24 June 2007. On 27 June, Blair resigned as [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] and was succeeded by Brown.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/output/Page4692.asp |title=Queen and Government |work=Website of the [[Monarchy of the United Kingdom|British Monarchy]]}}</ref>\n\nIf Brown had been opposed, Labour Party members would for the first time have directly elected a new Prime Minister.\n\n==Candidates==\n[[John McDonnell]] and [[Gordon Brown]] were the only candidates as the election process began with the nominations round. In order to secure a place on the ballot paper, candidates needed to submit their nominations to the [[National Executive Committee]] (NEC) by 17 May, each supported by at least 12.5% of [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] MPs (45 Labour MPs, including the candidate themselves). Brown, the only successfully nominated candidate, was declared leader at a special Labour conference on 24 June 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.labour.org.uk/leadership/nominations_close_-_1230_thursday_17_may |title=Labour leadership, close of nominations |date=2007-05-17 |work=Labour Party |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070921050327/http://www.labour.org.uk/leadership/nominations_close_-_1230_thursday_17_may |archivedate=2007-09-21 }}</ref>\n\n* Gordon Brown, [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/5376760.stm |title=Brown sets out leadership vision |author= |date=2006-09-26 |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref> long the favourite candidate to succeed [[Tony Blair]], received 313 nominations and was successfully nominated.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/6664063.stm |title= Brown 'humbled' by Labour backing |date=2007-05-17 |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref>\n* John McDonnell, chair of the [[Socialist Campaign Group]], pledged to merge Old Labour and New Labour into what he calls Real Labour, and to \"save the Labour government from itself\". He was hoping to get the backing of all those who had been backing [[Michael Meacher]], but did not do so;<ref>{{cite news |url=http://politics.guardian.co.uk/labourleadership/story/0,,2081121,00.html |title=Brown trying to prevent contest, claims McDonnell |date=2007-05-16 |work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher= |location=London |first=H\u00e9l\u00e8ne |last=Mulholland |accessdate=2010-05-07}}</ref> with 29 nominations, he was 16 short of the minimum required number, and was not successfully nominated.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/5179556.stm |title=Labour MP launches leadership bid |author= |date=2006-07-14 |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tni.org/detail_page.phtml?act_id=16809 |title=Challenging Brown from the Left? Meacher and McDonnell interviewed |author=Oscar Reyes |authorlink=Oscar Reyes |date=2007-05-11 |work=[[Red Pepper (magazine)|Red Pepper]] |publisher=[[Transnational Institute]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/UKNews1/idUKL1464496220070515 |title=McDonnell short for leadership race |author= |date=2007-05-15 |work=[[Reuters]] |publisher= }}</ref>\n* Michael Meacher (withdrew on 14 May 2007), former [[Secretary of State for the Environment, Transport and the Regions|Minister of State for the Environment]], was a candidate but withdrew after failing to get enough nominations. On 27 April 2007, he and McDonnell announced that whichever of them had the support of fewer Labour MPs at the point of Tony Blair's resignation would withdraw from the campaign and support the other.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6598683.stm |title=Left rivals unite to target Brown |author= |date=2007-04-27 |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref> On 10 May, they delayed their announcement because \"levels of support for each were too close to call\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/6642331.stm |title=Brown rivals delay bid decision |date=2007-05-10 |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref> Meacher gave his support to McDonnell on 14 May, but not all his supporters switched allegiance.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6652651.stm |title=Brown 'faces McDonnell challenge' |author= |date=2007-05-14 |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref>\n\n==Nominations and result==\n\n{| class =\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! colspan=2|Candidate !! Constituency !! Nominations !! Share !! Nominated?\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}};\"| || [[Gordon Brown]] || [[Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath (UK Parliament constituency)|Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath]] || 313 || 88.2% || {{Yes}}\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}};\"| || [[John McDonnell]] ||[[Hayes and Harlington (UK Parliament constituency)|Hayes and Harlington]]|| 29 || 8.2% || {{No}}\n|-\n|}\n\nOnly Gordon Brown attained over 45 nominations and was thus elected unopposed.\n\n==Suggested candidates who declined to run==\nDuring the months leading up to Tony Blair's resignation, media attention focused on a wide range of Labour politicians, most of whom publicly refused to stand:\n*[[Hilary Benn]], the [[Secretary of State for International Development]], was touted as a possible candidate to succeed Blair. However, he backed Gordon Brown.\n*[[Charles Clarke]], former [[Home Secretary]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.eveningnews24.co.uk/content/news/story.aspx?brand=ENOnline&category=News&tBrand=ENOnline&tCategory=news&itemid=NOED15%20Jan%202007%2013%3A04%3A56%3A433 |title=City MP says he won't fight Brown |date=2007-01-15 |work=[[Norwich Evening News]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928000707/http://www.eveningnews24.co.uk/content/news/story.aspx?brand=ENOnline&category=News&tBrand=ENOnline&tCategory=news&itemid=NOED15%20Jan%202007%2013%3A04%3A56%3A433 |archivedate=2007-09-28 }}</ref> had insisted he would stand if [[David Miliband]] did not, but later softened his position with praise for Brown, also saying that the Labour Party didn't have the appetite for a contest. He indicated that he would like to serve in a future Labour Cabinet;<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article1596687.ece |title=Clarke ready to run for leader |author=David Cracknell |author2=Isabel Oakeshott |date=2007-04-01 |work=[[The Sunday Times (UK)|Sunday Times]] |publisher= |location=London|author2-link=Isabel Oakeshott }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.politics.co.uk/news/features/labour-leadership/clarke-rules-out-leadership-with-praise-brown-$472810.htm |title=Clarke rules out leadership with praise for Brown |author= |date=2007-05-03 |publisher= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/6627153.stm |title=Clarke 'will not challenge Brown' |author= |date=2007-05-04 |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref> however, he was not offered any position, and went on to lose his seat in the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|subsequent general election in 2010]].\n*[[John Hutton (Labour MP)|John Hutton]], [[Secretary of State for Work and Pensions]], had said there should be a serious opponent to Brown, but on 6 May 2007 declared his support for Brown.<ref name=\"Will Blair and Brown get their way?\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/5319148.stm |title=Will Blair and Brown get their way? |author= |date=2006-09-06 |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref><ref name=\"Reid gives Brown clear run to No 10\">{{cite news |url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/reid-gives-brown-clear-run-to-no-10-1-1418911 |title=Reid gives Brown clear run to No 10 |author= |date=2007-05-06 |work=[[Scotland on Sunday]] |publisher= |accessdate=2019-05-19}}</ref>\n*[[Glenda Jackson]], MP for [[Hampstead and Highgate]] and former transport minister, had repeatedly threatened to stand as a stalking horse candidate against Blair from 2005 onwards; however, she backed Brown for the leadership.\n*[[Alan Johnson]], [[Secretary of State for Education]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6133276.stm |title=Johnson backing Brown for leader |author= |date=2006-11-09 |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref> In autumn 2006, he was (alongside [[John Reid, Baron Reid of Cardowan|John Reid]]) being touted as one of very few serious contenders, but later backed Brown.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/5341812.stm |title=Johnson fuels leadership speculation |author= |date=2006-09-26 |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref>\n*[[Lynne Jones]], MP for [[Birmingham Selly Oak (UK Parliament constituency)|Birmingham Selly Oak]], said that she would stand against Brown for the leadership as a leftwing candidate. However, she later backed [[John McDonnell]].\n*[[Alan Milburn]] ruled out standing for the Labour leadership on 11 May 2007, but previously had refused to rule it out.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/5237874.stm |title=Labour leadership contenders |author= |date=2007-05-10 |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://politics.guardian.co.uk/labourleadership/story/0,,2077454,00.html |title=Blair backs Brown as chancellor launches campaign |author=Deborah Summers and agencies |date=2007-05-11 |work=The Guardian |publisher= |location=London}}</ref>\n*David Miliband, [[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]]. Speculation that he would be persuaded to stand was intense during spring 2007, including suggestions that Blair saw him as a possible successor.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2007/03/27/nlabour27.xml |title=Labour slump may spark Miliband challenge |author= |date=2007-03-28 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |publisher= |location=London |accessdate=2010-05-07}}</ref> However, Miliband declined to stand, saying publicly that this had been his unwavering position for three years, and that he would vote for Brown.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6513013.stm |title=Beckett warns Miliband not to run |author= |date=2007-03-31 |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://politics.guardian.co.uk/labourleadership/story/0,,2054433,00.html |title=Miliband: I will not be seduced into leadership bid |author= |date=2007-04-11 |work=The Guardian |publisher= |location=London |first=Matthew |last=Tempest |accessdate=2010-05-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/6563747.stm |title=Miliband 'won't run for leader' |author= |date=2007-04-17 |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref>\n*John Reid, Home Secretary, had said he would not reveal whether he would stand or not until there was a vacancy, but on 6 May announced he would be voting for Brown and had decided to leave the Cabinet along with Blair.<ref name=\"Will Blair and Brown get their way?\"/><ref name=\"Reid gives Brown clear run to No 10\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/5377710.stm |title=Reid's end-of-rally job pitch |author= |date=2006-09-28 |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/6629877.stm |title=Reid to quit as home secretary |date=2007-05-06 |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref>\n*[[Jack Straw]], [[Leader of the House of Commons]], announced on 25 March that he would be running Gordon Brown's leadership campaign.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6492417.stm |title=Straw to run Brown leadership bid |author= |date=2007-03-25 |work=BBC News |publisher= }}</ref> He was appointed [[Lord Chancellor]] and [[Secretary of State for Justice]] in Brown's first cabinet.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/6247502.stm |title=Brown unveils huge Cabinet revamp |date=2007-06-28 |work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[2007 Labour Party deputy leadership election]]\n*[[2010 United Kingdom general election]]\n*[[Blair\u2013Brown deal]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.labour.org.uk/ Labour Party website]\n*{{citation |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/in_depth/uk_politics/2006/blair_succession/default.stm |title=Blair succession |publisher=BBC News |type=Special Report}}\n\n{{UK Labour Party}}\n{{Labour Party leadership election, 2007|state=expanded}}\n{{Gordon Brown}}\n\n[[Category:2007 elections in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) leadership elections|2007]]\n[[Category:Single-candidate elections]]\n", "name_user": "BRFC4104", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSuggested candidates who declined to run", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2007_Labour_Party_leadership_election_(UK)"}
{"title_page": "5th Battalion, Royal Northumberland Fusiliers", "text_new": "{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name = 2nd Northumberland Rifle Volunteer Corps<br>5th Bn, Royal Northumberland Fusiliers<br>53rd (Royal Northumberland Fusiliers) S/L Rgt, RA<br>638th (Royal Northumberland Fusiliers) Rgt, RA<br>588 (Royal Northumberland Fusiliers) LAA Rgt,RA\n| image = Royal_Northumberland_Fusiliers_Cap_Badge.jpg\n| caption = [[Royal Northumberland Fusiliers]] cap badge\n| dates = 1861\u20141918<br>1920\u20141945<br>1947\u20141950\n| country = {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n| allegiance = \n| branch = {{army|United Kingdom}}\n*[[Royal Northumberland Fusiliers]]\n*[[Royal Artillery]]\n| type = [[Infantry]]<br>[[Searchlight]]<br>Light Anti-Aircraft Artillery\n| role = Air defence artillery\n| size = [[Battalion]]/[[Regiment]]\n| command_structure = \n| garrison = [[Walker-on-Tyne]]\n| nickname = Tynemouth Rifles\n| patron = \n| motto = \n| colors = \n| march = \n| mascot = \n| battles = [[Second Boer War|South African War]]<br>[[World War I]]<br>[[World War II]]\n| anniversaries = \n| current_commander = \n| ceremonial_chief = \n| colonel_of_the_regiment = \n| notable_commanders = \n}}{{Short description|The 2nd Northumberland RVC, later 5th Btn, Royal Northumberland Fus was a reserve army unit of the [[British Army]] which saw service during the world wars.}}\nThe '''2nd Northumberland Rifle Volunteer Corps''', also referred to as the Tynemouth Rifles, was an infantry unit of Britain's part-time force, the [[Territorial Army (United Kingdom)|Territorial Army]]. The corps was raised during the expansion of the [[Volunteer Force|Volunteer movement]] in the 1850s and then served with the [[Territorial Force]] during [[World War I]]. It converted to an anti-aircraft role just prior to [[World War II]], and continued to serve until it was amalgamated in 1950.\n\n== Volunteer Force ==\nThe enthusiasm for the Volunteer movement following an invasion scare in 1859 saw the creation of many Rifle Volunteer Corps (RVCs) composed of part-time soldiers eager to supplement the Regular [[British Army]] in time of need.<ref>Beckett.</ref><ref>Westlake, ''Rifle Volunteers''.</ref> One of these new corps was the 1st Northumberland RVC (also known as the Northumberland Rifles) formed in [[North Shields]] and [[Tynemouth]] on 16 August 1859 by coal-owner Edward Potter of [[Cramlington]]. It took some moral courage to appear in the street in Volunteer uniform: members of the 1st Northumberland RVC were sneered at as 'noodles'. However, the movement continued to grow: in February 1860 the 1st absorbed the 2nd Northumberland RVC of three companies, also formed at Tynemouth on 4 January that year. In August 1861 it split to form the 1st (Tynemouth), 8th (three companies at [[Walker-on-Tyne]]) and 9th (Cramlington) Northumberland RVCs, which were all placed in the '''2nd Administrative Battalion of Northumberland Rifle Volunteers'''. The 1st disbanded in October 1862 and the 9th in December 1864, but the '''8th (Walker) Northumberland RVC''' thrived. The HQ of the 2nd Admin Battalion moved to Walker after the disbandment of the 1st; it was disbanded in 1865 and the 8th continued as an independent corps with James Anderson, a former [[Ensign_(rank)#United_Kingdom|ensign]] in the [[30th Foot]], as [[Lieutenant colonel (United Kingdom)|lieutenant-colonel]] in command. A number of its officers were drawn from the prominent Tyneside family of Swan.<ref name=\":12\">Westlake, ''Rifle Volunteers'', pp. 191\u20133.</ref><ref>Beckett, pp. 63, 96 and Appendix VII.</ref><ref name = List>''Army List''.</ref><ref name=\":02\">Frederick, Volume I, pp. 276-7.</ref><ref name=\":22\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20071021105818/http://www.regiments.org/regiments/uk/volmil-england/vinf-no/nd-5.htm 5th Battalion, The Royal Northumberland Fusiliers at Regiments.org, retrieved 15 February 2020.]</ref><ref>Beckett, p. 63; Appendix VII.</ref> During this period, the battalion was organised as;<ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":22\" />\n\n* Battalion Headquarters in [[Tynemouth]] ''\u2013 HQ moving to [[Newcastle upon Tyne]] in 1863''\n* 1st (Tynemouth) Northumberland RVC \u2013 ''raised 16 August 1859: three coys separated Aug 1861 to form 8th RVC in Walker and one coy separated to form 9th RVC in [[Cramlington]]: disbanded Oct 1862''\n* 8th (Walker) Northumberland RVC \u2013 ''formed Aug 1861 from three coys of the 1st RVC''\n* 9th (Cramlington) Northumberland RVC \u2013 ''formed Aug 1861 from one coy of 1st RVC: disbanded Dec 1864''\n\nUnder the scheme of 'localisation' introduced by the [[Cardwell Reforms]] in 1873, the Northumberland and [[Newcastle upon Tyne]] RVCs, together with the two Regular battalions of the Northumberland Fusiliers and the [[Militia and Volunteers of Northumberland|Northumberland Militia]], constituted Brigade No 1, based at Newcastle in the County of Northumberland sub-district of [[Northern Command (United Kingdom)|Northern District]]. While the sub-districts were referred to as 'brigades', they were purely administrative organisations and the Volunteers were excluded from the 'mobilisation' part of the Cardwell system, though they carried out joint manoeuvres.<ref name = List/><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20051230125426/http://www.regiments.org/regiments/uk/depot/1873.htm Training Depots, 1873\u20131881 at Regiments.org.]</ref> Lieutenant-Colonel Anderson retired in 1875 and was appointed [[Colonel_(United_Kingdom)#Honorary_Colonel|Honorary Colonel]] of the battalion; he was succeeded in command by Henry Swan who ran the Walker shipyard of [[Charles Mitchell (shipbuilder)|Charles Mitchell]] and later [[Armstrong Whitworth]]. Swan remained in command until 1902.<ref name = List/><ref>[https://www.gracesguide.co.uk/Henry_Frederick_Swan Henry Frederick Swan at Grace's Guides.]</ref>\n\nWhen the RVCs were consolidated nationwide on 3 September 1880, the 8th RVC was re-numbered as the '''2nd Northumberland Rifle Volunteer Corps''' with companies designated as 'A' to 'F'.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":22\" /> After the [[Childers Reforms]] the RVCs became Volunteer Battalions of their affiliated Regular Army regiment and in 1883 the 2nd Northumberland RVC became the '''2nd Volunteer Battalion, Northumberland Fusiliers''' and  wore a scarlet coat with Gosling green [[Facing colour|facings]].<ref name=\":12\"/><ref name = List/> The [[Stanhope Memorandum]] of December 1888 proposed a more comprehensive Mobilisation Scheme for Volunteer units, which would assemble in their own brigades at key points in case of war. In peacetime these brigades provided a structure for collective training.<ref>Beckett, pp. 135, 185\u20136.</ref><ref>Dunlop, pp. 60\u20131.</ref> Under this scheme the 2nd and 3rd VBs of the Northumberland Fusiliers and the five [[Durham Light Infantry]] VBs formed the Tyne and Tees Brigade.<ref name = List/>\n\nIn 1894, K Company from the 1st Volunteer Battalion at [[Newburn]] (formed in 1885) was transferred to the 2nd as G Company. The following year the 2nd VB formed a new company at [[Wallsend]] and by 1900 the battalion had grown to ten companies, at Walker (4), Newburn (2), Wallsend (2) and [[Gosforth]] (2).<ref name=\":12\"/>\n\nBetween 1900\u201302, volunteers from the 2nd VB went to [[South Africa]] and participated with their Regular counterparts in the 1st and 2nd Battalions.  As a reward for their service, the battalion was granted its first battle honour: ''South Africa 1900-02'''''.'''  Engagements during this period included service in the [[Orange Free State]], service in [[Transvaal Colony|Transvaal]], and later the [[Battle of Rustenburg]].<ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":32\">Westlake, ''Territorials'', p. 43.</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071023193049/http://regiments.org/wars/19thcent/99za-abw.htm  Second Anglo-Boer War 1899-1902 at Regiments.org, retrieved 16 February 2020.]</ref>\n\n== Territorial Force ==\nIn 1907, [[Secretary of State for War]] [[Richard Haldane, 1st Viscount Haldane|Richard Haldane]] announced a series of Army reforms, which would affect mostly the [[Volunteer Force|Volunteers]] and [[Imperial Yeomanry|Yeomanry]]. These two groups were merged to form the [[Territorial Force]] on 1 April 1908.  As part of these reforms, all of the volunteer battalions became numbered battalions of their patrent regiments. The battalion was renamed as the '''5th Battalion, The Northumberland Fusiliers''' and subsequently re-organised as follows:<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":32\" /><ref>Westlake, ''Territorials'', Introduction</ref><ref>[http://www.geograph.org.uk/article/WW1-Great-War-Centenary---Drill-Halls/8#northumberland Northumberland at Great War Centenary Drill Halls]. Retrieved 16 February 2020.</ref><ref name = List/><ref>Dunlop, Chapter 14.</ref><ref>[http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/28121/supplements/2153 ''London Gazette'' 20 March 1908.]</ref>\n* Battalion Headquarters in Walker\n* A\u2013C Companies in Walker\n* D\u2013F Companies in [[Wallsend]]\n* G Company in [[Gosforth]] with detachments in [[West Moor]] and [[Seaton Burn]]\n* H Company in Gosforth\n\nAnother organisational change of the reforms of 1908 was the creation in the TF of 14 divisions, 14 mounted brigades, and coastal defence troops. One of these new divisions was the [[Northumbrian Division]] (later the 50th), and in this division was the [[Northumbrian Brigade]] (later the [[149th (Northumberland) Brigade|149th]]). The 5th Bn along with the 4th, 6th, and 7th bns of the Royal Northumberland Fusiliers were all part of this brigade.<ref name = Becke50>Becke, Pt 2a, pp. 93\u2013100.</ref><ref name=\":42\">[http://www.longlongtrail.co.uk/army/order-of-battle-of-divisions/50th-northumbrian-division/ 50th (Northumbrian) Division at The Long, Long Trail, retrieved 16 February 2020.]</ref><ref name=\":52\">[http://www.longlongtrail.co.uk/army/regiments-and-corps/the-british-infantry-regiments-of-1914-1918/northumberland-fusiliers/ Northumberland Fusiliers at The Long, Long Trail, retrieved 16 February 2020]</ref>\n\n== World War I ==\n===Mobilisation===\nIn July of 1914, as the international situation worsened, the [[British Armed Forces]] were on high alert as the [[Imperial German Army]] moved towards the neutral nation of the [[Kingdom of Belgium]], of which the [[United Kingdom]] protected under the [[Treaty of London (1839)|Treaty of London]]. When German forces crossed into [[Belgium]], the [[United Kingdom]] declared war on [[Germany]] and later the rest of the [[Central Powers]]. At the time the units of the Northumbrian Division were at their annual training camp in [[North Wales]]. On 3 August they were ordered to return to their respective headquarters, where at 17.00 next day they received orders to [[Mobilization|mobilise]]. The units went to their war stations along the coast, where there were numerous alerts. In October the division became part of [[Central Force]] in Home Defence and manned the [[River Tyne|Tyne]] Defences.<ref name = Becke50/><ref name=\":52\"/><ref>Wyrall, p.4.</ref>\n\nOn the outbreak of war, TF units were invited to volunteer for Overseas Service. The large majority of the Northumbrian Division accepted. On 15 August the [[War Office]] (WO) issued instructions to separate those men who had signed up for Home Service only, and form these into reserve units. On 31 August, the formation of a reserve or 2nd Line unit was authorised for each 1st Line unit where 60 per cent or more of the men had volunteered for Overseas Service. The titles of these 2nd Line units would be the same as the original, but distinguished by a '2/' prefix. In this way duplicate battalions, brigades and divisions were created, mirroring those TF formations being sent overseas.<ref name = Becke63>Becke, Pt 2b, pp. 49\u201354.</ref><ref name = Trail63>[http://www.longlongtrail.co.uk/army/order-of-battle-of-divisions/63rd-2nd-northumbrian-division/ 63rd (2nd Northumbrian) Division at Long, Long Trail.]</ref><ref>Becke, Pt 2b, p. 6.</ref><ref>Wyrall, pp. 4\u20135.</ref>\n\n=== 1/5th Battalion ===\n[[File:Northumberland Fusiliers at Thiepval Sept 1916 IWM Q 1349.jpg|thumb|Northumberland Fusiliers in a reserve trench at [[Thiepval]], September 1916.]]\nIn  April 1915 the 1/5th Battalion moved to [[France]] and saw action during some notable battles including:<ref name=\":42\" /><ref name=\":52\" /><ref name=\":0\">[https://www.forces-war-records.co.uk/units/217/royal-northumberland-fusiliers Unit History: Royal Northumberland Fusiliers at Forces War Records, retrieved 16 February 2020.]</ref><ref>Wyrall.</ref>\n* 1915: [[Battle of St Julien]], [[Battle of Frezenberg|Battle of Frezenburg]], and [[Battle of Bellewaarde|Battle of Bellewaarde Ridge]]\n* 1916: [[Battle of Flers-Courcelette]], [[Battle of Morval]], and [[Battle of Le Transloy|Battle of the Transloy Ridges]]\n* 1917: [[Battle of Arras (1917)|First Battle of the Scarpe]], Capture of [[Wancourt]] Ridge, [[Second Battle of the Scarpe]], and [[Second Battle of Passchendaele]]\n* 1918: [[Battle of St Quentin Canal|Battle of St Quentin]], [[Operation_Michael#Actions_at_the_Somme_crossings,_24\u201325_March|Actions at the Somme Crossings]], [[Battle of Rosieres]], [[Battle of Estaires]], [[Battle of Hazebrouck]], and [[Battle of the Aisne]]\n\nFollowing the armistice on 11 November 1918, the battalion was reduced to a [[Cadre (military)|cadre]] on 15 July and disembodied on 6 November 1918.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":42\" /><ref name=\":52\" />\n\n=== 2/5th Battalion ===\nThe 2/5th Battalion was formed in [[Blyth, Northumberland|Blyth]] along with the 2/4th on the 22\u201323 November 1914 just before their respective first line battalions were preparing to go overseas.  This new battalion joined the [[188th (2/1st Northumberland) Brigade]] in the newly formed 2nd line [[63rd (2nd Northumbrian) Division]] in January 1915.  In July 1916 the division was divided, and the battalion became independent and eventually joined the [[217th Brigade (United Kingdom)|217th Brigade]] in the [[72nd Division (United Kingdom)|72nd Division]]. Finally, on 6 December 1918 the battalion was disbanded while stationed in [[Ipswich]] and replaced by the 264th (Infantry) Battalion, [[Training Reserve]].<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":52\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name = Becke63/><ref name = Trail63/>\n\n=== 5th (Reserve) Battalion ===\nThe '''3/5th Battalion''', later 5th (Reserve) Btn, was the last of the duplicates formed with the 3/4th, 3/6th, and 3/7th formed in June 1915.  On 8 April 1916 the battalions were all redesignated as 'reserve', and became the 5th (Reserve) Battalion.  On 1 September 1918 the battalion was absorbed into the 4th (Reserve) Battalion.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":52\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Interwar ==\nWhen the [[Territorial Force]] was disembodied after the end of [[World War I]], the army was left with just the regulars, most of which were under-strength or just at [[Cadre (military)|cadre]] size. On 7 February 1920 the TF and most of its units were reconstituted, including the 5th Battalion, The Northumberland Fusiliers at Walker-on-Tyne with 'A', 'B', 'C', and 'D' Companies. Once again it formed part of 149th (Northumberland) Brigade in 50th (Northumbrian) Division.<ref>''Titles and Designations'' 1927.</ref> In 1921 the TF was reorganised as the [[Territorial Army (United Kingdom)|Territorial Army]]. On 3 June 1935 as part of [[George V]]\u2019s silver jubilee celebrations the regiment was granted a Royal title along with three other Regiments and became the [[Royal Northumberland Fusiliers]], and the battalion was re-named likewise.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== 5th Battalion, Royal Northumberland Fusiliers (53rd Searchlight Regiment) ===\nIn the late 1930s the increasing need for anti-aircraft (AA) defence for Britain's cities was addressed by converting a number of TA infantry battalions into searchlight (S/L) units, which accelerated after the [[Munich Crisis]]. The 5th Battalion was one of those selected, and was converted on 1 November 1938 as '''5th Battalion, Royal Northumberland Fusiliers (53rd Searchlight Regiment)''', organised as follows:<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":2\">Frederick, p. 869.</ref><ref name=\":62\">The Monthly Army List, ''[https://deriv.nls.uk/dcn23/1055/2061/105520619.23.pdf August 1939] (pdf)'', [[London]]: His Majesty's Stationary Office (1939), Retrieved 16 February 2020.</ref>\n* Battalion Headquarters, Church Street Drill hall, [[Walker-on-Tyne]] under [[Lieutenant Colonel]] W H Leete, [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|DFC]], [[Territorial Decoration|TD]]\n* 408th S/L Company under [[Major]] G. M. I. Stanley\n* 409th S/L Company under [[Major]] F. H. Phillips\n* 410th S/L Company under [[Major]] A. E. B. Plummer, [[Military Cross|MC]]\n* Affiliation with Armstrong-Whitworth (Walker) Cadet Unit (placed under administrative command)\n\nUnlike some of the infantry battalions previously converted to the AA S/L role, which had transferred to the [[Royal Engineers]] (RE), the 5th Bn remained part of the Royal Northumberland Fusiliers for the time being.\n\nFollowing its change of role, the battalion was placed under the command of the [[30th (Northumbrian) Anti-Aircraft Brigade]]. This was subordinated to [[3rd Anti-Aircraft Division (United Kingdom)|3rd Anti-Aircraft Division]], but by the outbreak of war came under a newly-formed  [[7th Anti-Aircraft Division (United Kingdom)|7th AA Division]] tasked with covering  [[North East England]].<ref name = List/><ref name=\":3\">[http://www.patriotfiles.com/index.php?name=Sections&req=viewarticle&artid=6697&page=1 British Anti-Aircraft Command, TA on 3 September 1939] at the [http://www.patriotfiles.com Patriot Files]. Retrieved 16 February 2020.</ref><ref>Routledge, Table LX, p. 378.</ref><ref>Pettibone, p. 298.</ref>\n\n== World War II ==\n===Mobilisation===\nIn February 1939 the existing AA defences came under the control of a new [[Anti-Aircraft Command]]. In June, as the international situation worsened, a partial mobilisation of the TA was begun in a process known as 'couverture', whereby each AA unit did a month's tour of duty in rotation to man selected AA gun and S/L positions. On 24 August, ahead of the declaration of war, AA Command was fully mobilised at its war stations. The 5th Battalion was deployed to support the Newcastle Gun Defence Area (GDA). The S/L layouts had been planned on a spacing of {{convert|3500|yd|m}}, but due to equipment shortages this was extended to {{convert|6000|yd|m}}.<ref>Routledge, pp. 388-9.</ref><ref>Routledge, pp. 65\u20136, 371, 388-9; Table LIX, p. 377.</ref>\n\nOn 1 August 1940 all of the RE and infantry AA units were brought under command of the [[Royal Artillery]]. Therefore the battalion was re-named as the '''53rd (Royal Northumberland Fusiliers) Searchlight Regiment, Royal Artillery''' with its companies (408, 409, and 410) becoming batteries.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":1\">Litchfield, p. 195.</ref><ref>[http://www.ra39-45.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/sl/page33.html 53 (R Northumberland Fus) Searchlight Regt RA (TA)] at [http://www.ra39-45.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk Royal Artillery 1939-45], [https://web.archive.org/web/20090107170758/http://www.ra39-45.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/sl/page33.html Archived] on 7 January 2009 at the [https://web.archive.org Wayback Machine]. Retrieved 16 February 2020.</ref><ref name = FarnM>Farndale, Annex M.</ref> During this re-organisation, [[Anti-Aircraft Command]] (AA Command) was also being overhauled, with many new brigades and divisions being formed, one of them being the [[57th Light Anti-Aircraft Brigade (United Kingdom)|57th Light Anti-Aircraft Brigade]] formed on 25 August 1939 which initially only controlled the Light AA (LAA) units of the division.<ref>David A. Ryan, Dr. Graham Watson, and Robert Michel, [http://niehorster.org/017_britain/39_commands/aa-07.html 7th Anti-Aircraft Division, Anti-Aircraft Command] at [http://niehorster.org World War II Armed Forces - Orders of Battle and Organizations]. Retrieved 16 February 2020.</ref><ref>Frederick, p. 1050.</ref><ref>[http://www.ra39-45.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/home/page54.html 7 AA Division] at [http://www.ra39-45.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk Royal Artillery 1939-45], [https://web.archive.org/web/20140224020652/http://www.ra39-45.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/home/page54.html Archived] on 24 February 2014 at the [https://web.archive.orgo.uk/home/page54.html Wayback Machine]. Retrieved 16 February 2020.</ref>\n[[File:The British Army in the United Kingdom 1939-45 H35912.jpg|thumb|150 cm Anti-aircraft searchlight equipped with SLC (AA Radar No 2) during World War II.]]\n===Newcastle Blitz===\nDuring the ''[[Luftwaffe]]'' night-bombing campaign against British cities in the winter of 1940\u201341 ([[The Blitz]]) 30 AA Bde controlled the AA guns in the Newcastle GDA, while 57 AA Bde controlled the S/L layout, including 53rd S/L Regiment. The regiment served through the [[Newcastle Blitz]].<ref>Routledge, Table LXV, p. 397.</ref><ref>Farndale, Annex D.</ref><ref name = Orbat79>Order of Battle of Non-Field Force Units in the United Kingdom, Part 27: AA Command, 12 May 1941, with amendments, [[The National Archives (United Kingdom)|The National Archives (TNA), Kew]], file WO 212/79.</ref> In November 1940 AA Command changed its S/L layouts to clusters of three lights to improve illumination, but this meant that the clusters had to be spaced {{convert|10400|yd|m}} apart. The cluster system was an attempt to improve the chances of picking up enemy bombers and keeping them illuminated for engagement by AA guns or [[Royal Air Force]] (RAF) [[Night fighter]]s. Eventually, one light in each cluster was to be equipped with [[Searchlight Control radar]] (SLC) and act as 'master light', but the radar equipment was still in short supply.<ref>Routledge, p. 393.</ref><ref>Farndale, p. 107.</ref>\n\nOn 17 April 1941, 565 S/L Bty was formed under the [[236th Searchlight Training Regiment, Royal Artillery|236th Searchlight Training Rgt]] at [[Oswestry]] from a [[Cadre (military)|cadre]] provided by 53rd S/L Regiment, and shortly joined, and regimented on 12 August 1941.  On 18 February 1942, the regiment had a small name change, to become the '''53rd Searchlight Regiment, Royal Artillery (Royal Northumberland Fusiliers)'''.<ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":4\">Frederick, Volume II, p. 862.</ref><ref>Frederick, Volume II, p. 869.</ref>\n\nBy December 1941 the regiment had moved to [[43rd Anti-Aircraft Brigade (United Kingdom)|43 AA Bde]], still in 7th AA Division but now deployed covering [[Wearside]] and [[Teesside]].<ref>Order of Battle of Non-Field Force Units in the United Kingdom, Part 27: AA Command, 2 December 1941, TNA file WO 212/80.</ref> It remained under 43 AA Bde until August 1942 when it returned to 30 AA Bde<ref> Order of Battle of Non-Field Force Units in the United Kingdom, Part 27: AA Command, 14 May 1942, with amendments, TNA file WO 212/81.</ref><ref>Order of Battle of Non-Field Force Units in the United Kingdom, Part 27: AA Command, 1 October 1942, TNA file WO 212/82.</ref><ref>Order of Battle of Non-Field Force Units in the United Kingdom, Part 27: AA Command, 13 March 1943, TNA file WO 212/83.</ref><ref> Order of Battle of AA Command, 1 August 1943, TNA file WO 212/84.</ref>\n\n===Operation Diver===\nBy  late 1943, AA Command was being forced to release manpower for overseas service, particularly [[Operation Overlord]] (the planned Allied invasion of Normandy) and most S/L regiments lost one of their four batteries. 565 S/L Battery began to disband on 25 February 1944, which it completed by 24 March.<ref name=\":22\" /><ref name = Rout408>Routledge, pp. 408\u201310.</ref> In March 1944, 30 AA Bde HQ was transferred to the south of England; 53rd S/L Rgt also went south, but joined [[47th Anti-Aircraft Brigade (United Kingdom)|47 AA Bde]] in [[2nd Anti-Aircraft Group (United Kingdom)|2 AA Group]]. 2 AA Group was responsible for defending the 'Overlord' assembly camps, depots and embarkation ports and was planning for the expected onslaught of [[V-1 flying bomb]]s against London. Meanwhile, the group had to deal with a sharp increase in ''Luftwaffe'' air raids trying to reach London, which continued until May.<ref name = Pile>[https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/38149/page/5973 Pile.]</ref><ref name = Rout408/><ref>Order of Battle of AA Command, 27 April 1944, TNA file WO 212/85.</ref>\n\nOn 13 June, a week after the Overlord fleets had left to launch [[D Day]], the first V-1s appeared over southern England. 2 AA Group deployed its Light AA guns alongside S/L positions, hoping that the SLC could guide the LAA guns at night. By day, the S/L positions used their AA [[Light machine guns]] in an effort to bring down the fast-moving missiles. The early success rate was low, but later fighter aircraft and radar-directed Heavy AA guns achieved high rates of success against V-1s.<ref name = Pile/><ref name = Rout408/>  \n\n===638th (Royal Northumberland Fusiliers) Infantry Regiment, RA===\nIn January 1945, the diminishing threat of the [[Luftwaffe]] coupled with a manpower shortage in [[21st Army Group]], particularly in the infantry, led to the conversion of surplus anti-aircraft and coastal artillery regiments in the UK into infantry units. 53rd Searchlight Regiment was one of the regiments selected but it did not revert to its original title, instead becoming '''638th (Royal Northumberland Fusiliers) Regiment, Royal Artillery''' on 23 January 1945.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name = FarnM/><ref name=\":5\">Frederick, Volume II, p. 883.</ref><ref>[http://www.ra39-45.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/infantry/page38.html 638 (R Northumberland Fus) Regt RA (TA)] at [http://www.ra39-45.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk Royal Artillery 1939-45], [https://web.archive.org/web/20090107112151/http://www.ra39-45.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/infantry/page38.html Archived] on 7 January 2009 at the [https://web.archive.org Wayback Machine]. Retrieved 16 February 2020.</ref>\n\nThe regiment was attached to [[38th Light Anti-Aircraft Brigade (United Kingdom)|38 AA Bde]], which was converting into [[304th Infantry Brigade (United Kingdom)|304 Infantry Brigade]]. After infantry training, including a short period attached to [[55th (West Lancashire) Infantry Division]], the brigade was moved into the [[War Office]] Reserve, and shipped to [[Norway]], landing on 7 June 1945 and joining [[Norway Command]] following the liberation of that country ([[Operation Doomsday]]).<ref>Joslen, p. 400.</ref> The regiment was still in Norway on 15 November 1945 when 638 Rgt began the process of entering suspended animation, completing the process on 13 December.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Postwar ==\nFollowing the end of hostilities most territorial artillery regiments had been placed in suspended animation by late 1946. On 1 January 1947 most of these regiments were reconstituted and many new regiments were formed as part of the reformed and re-organised TA, with new numbers according to the renumbering plan for the complete re-designation of all RA units, both regular and territorial.  In accordance with this, the light anti-aircraft (LAA) regiments were assigned numbers between 512 and 588. The 5th Btn was reformed as '''588th (Royal Northumberland Fusiliers) Light Anti-Aircraft Regiment, Royal Artillery''', and followed the new standard RA organisation, which consisted of RHQ, P, Q, and R Batteries, all of which were based in Walker on Tyne. The regiment provided the LAA component of the TA's [[50th (Northumbrian) Infantry Division]].<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name = FarnM/><ref name=\":6\">Litchfield, pp. 5-6.</ref><ref>Frederick, Volume II, p. 1024.</ref><ref>[http://www.orbat.info/history/historical/uk/ta47.html  Watson, ''TA 1947''.]</ref><ref>Litchfield, Appendix 5.</ref><ref name = 45on>[http://british-army-units1945on.co.uk/territorial-army-royal-artillery/564-591-regiments.html 564\u2013591 Rgts RA at British Army 1945 on.]</ref>\n\nOn 1 September 1950 the regiment was converted back to infantry and simultaneously merged with the 4th Btn to form the '''4th/5th Battalion, The Royal Northumberland Fusiliers'''.  In 1967 the battalion's [[Territorial and Army Volunteer Reserve]] (TAVR) successors were A (Royal Northumberland Fusiliers) Company, [[Fusilier Volunteers]] and the 4th/5th/6th (Territorial) Battalion, [[Royal Northumberland Fusiliers]] both of which were eventually expanded into the [[6th (Northumberland) Battalion, The Royal Regiment of Fusiliers]].  The Northumberland TA successors are currently part of 'X' and 'Z' companies in the [[5th (Volunteer) Battalion, The Royal Regiment of Fusiliers]].<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":6\" /><ref name = 45on/><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20060117220814/http://www.regiments.org:80/regiments/uk/volmil-england/vinf-no/nd-4.htm 4/5th Bn Northumberland Fusiliers at Regiments.org.]</ref><ref>[https://www.britishbadgeforum.com/forums/attachment.php?attachmentid=106964&d=1401909298 New Title for Reserve Army Units]; [https://www.britishbadgeforum.com/forums/attachment.php?attachmentid=106965&d=1401909330 T&AVR Category II: The Volunteers], The Territorial Magazine, April 1967. Retrieved 16 February 2020.</ref><ref>[https://www.britishbadgeforum.com/forums/attachment.php?attachmentid=106964&d=1401909298 New Title for Reserve Army Units]; [https://www.britishbadgeforum.com/forums/attachment.php?attachmentid=106969&d=1401909545 T&AVR Category III: The Territorials], The Territorial Magazine, April 1967. Retrieved 16 February 2020.</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071020113534/http://www.regiments.org/regiments/uk/volmil-england/vinf-no/nd-4.htm 4th Battalion, The Royal Northumberland Fusiliers at Regiments.org,  retrieved 16 February 2020.]</ref><ref>[http://www.orbat.info/history/historical/uk/ta47.html Watson, ''TA 1947'', retrieved 16 February 2020.]</ref><ref>Wienand Drenth, ''[https://www.orbat85.nl/documents/The%20Territorial%20Army%201967-2000.pdf The Territorial Army 1967-2000] (pdf)'', 2000: [[Eindhoven]], [[Kingdom of the Netherlands]].</ref><ref>[https://www.army.mod.uk/who-we-are/corps-regiments-and-units/infantry/royal-regiment-of-fusiliers/ The Royal Regiment of Fusiliers], [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]], [[London]].</ref>\n\n== Personalities ==\n'''Commanding Officers'''\n\nThose commanding officers which served during [[World War I]]:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ww1infantrycos.co.uk/northumberland.html|title=First World War Infantry Battalion Commanding Officers - Page 13|website=www.ww1infantrycos.co.uk|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\n''1/5th Battalion''\n\n* [[Lieutenant Colonel]] David Ross MacDonald, 4 August 1914 > replaced\n* [[Colonel]] Arthur Horsman Coles, 25 November 1915 > replaced\n* [[Lieutenant Colonel]] Hermann Luhrs, 26 November 1915 > replaced\n* [[Lieutenant Colonel]] Francis Charles Turner, 14 March 1916 > replaced\n* [[Lieutenant Colonel]] Nicholas Irwin Wright, 27 September 1916 > invalided\n* [[Lieutenant Colonel]] Arnold Irwin, 17 March 1918 > wounded\n* [[Lieutenant Colonel]] Ivan Marshall Tweedy 1 May 1918 > replaced\n* [[Lieutenant Colonel]] Henry Robert Brown 13 July 1918 > remained CO\n\n''2/5th Battalion''\n\n* [[Lieutenant Colonel]] David Ross MacDonald, 25 November 1914 > replaced\n* [[Lieutenant Colonel]] Francis William Iles 28 August 1915 > replaced\n* [[Lieutenant Colonel]] Lionel Grant Oliver, 16 May 1916 > replaced\n\n''3/5th (5th Reserve) Battalion''\n\n* [[Lieutenant Colonel]] Thomas Joseph Carlile, 15 June 1915 > replaced\n\n'''Honorary Colonels'''\n\nThe battalion's (later regiment's) [[Colonel_(United_Kingdom)#Honorary_Colonel|Honorary Colonels]] included:<ref name = List/><ref name=\":22\" />\n* 1875\u20131900, [[Colonel_(United_Kingdom)|Colonel]] James Anderson, former CO\n* 1900\u20131902, Vacant\n* 1902\u20131908, [[Brevet (military)|Brevet]] Colonel Henry Frederick Swan, [[Companions of the Order of the Bath|CB]], [[Volunteer Officers' Decoration|VD]]\n* 1908\u20131910, Vacant\n* 1910\u20131916, [[Lieutenant colonel (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant-Colonel]] [[Matthew White Ridley, 2nd Viscount Ridley]], [[Northumberland Hussars]]\n* 1916\u20131928, Vacant\n* 1928\u20131938, Honorary [[Brigadier General]] Hubert Horatio Shirley Morant, [[Distinguished Service Order|DSO]]\n* 1938\u20131950, Colonel Bernard Peatfield, [[OBE]], [[Military Cross|MC]], [[Territorial Decoration|TD]], DL (continued 1950 into 4th/5th Btn)\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n== References ==\n{{refbegin|2}}\n* Maj A.F. Becke,''History of the Great War: Order of Battle of Divisions, Part 2a: The Territorial Force Mounted Divisions and the 1st-Line Territorial Force Divisions (42\u201356)'', London: HM Stationery Office, 1935/Uckfield: Naval & Military Press, 2007, {{ISBN|1-847347-39-8}}.\n* Maj A.F. Becke,''History of the Great War: Order of Battle of Divisions, Part 2b: The 2nd-Line Territorial Force Divisions (57th\u201369th), with the Home-Service Divisions (71st\u201373rd) and 74th and 75th Divisions,'' London: HM Stationery Office, 1937/Uckfield: Naval & Military Press, 2007, {{ISBN|1-847347-39-8}}.\n* Ian F.W. Beckett, ''Riflemen Form: A Study of the Rifle Volunteer Movement 1859\u20131908'', Aldershot: Ogilby Trusts, 1982, {{ISBN|0 85936 271 X}}.\n* Col John K. Dunlop, ''The Development of the British Army 1899\u20131914'', London: Methuen, 1938.\n* Gen Sir [[Martin Farndale]], ''History of the Royal Regiment of Artillery: The Years of Defeat: Europe and North Africa, 1939\u20131941'', [[Woolwich]], UK: Royal Artillery Institution, 1988/[[London]], UK: Brasseys, 1996, {{ISBN|1-85753-080-2}}.\n* J.B.M. Frederick, ''Lineage Book of British Land Forces 1660-1978'', Volume I,  [[Wakefield]], UK: Microform Academic Publishers, 1984, {{ISBN|1-85117-007-3}}.\n* J.B.M. Frederick, ''Lineage Book of British Land Forces 1660-1978'', Volume II, Wakefield, UK: Microform Academic Publishers, 1984 {{ISBN|1-85117-008-1}}.\n* Lt-Col H.F. Joslen, ''Orders of Battle, Second World War, 1939\u20131945''. London, UK:  Her Majesty's Stationery Office, 1960/London Stamp Exchange, 1990, {{ISBN|0-948130-03-2}}/Uckfield, UK: Naval & Military Press, 2003, {{ISBN|1-843424-74-6}}.\n* Norman E. H. Litchfield, ''The Territorial Artillery 1908 - 1988'',  [[Nottingham]], UK: The Sherwood Press, 1992, {{ISBN|0-9508205-2-0}}.\n* Charles D. Pettibone, ''The Organization and Order of Battle of Militaries in World War II'', Volume II, ''The British Commonwealth'', [[Victoria (British Columbia)|Victoria]], [[Canada]], Trafford Publishing, 2006, {{ISBN|141208567-5}}.\n* [https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/38149/page/5973 Gen Sir Frederick Pile's despatch: 'The Anti-Aircraft Defence of the United Kingdom from 28th July, 1939, to 15th April, 1945' ''London Gazette'' 18 December 1947.]\n* [[Brigadier]] N. W. Routledge. ''History of the Royal Regiment of Artillery: Anti-Aircraft Artillery 1914-55''. (1994). London, UK: Brassey's Publishing. {{ISBN|1-85753-099-3}}.\n* War Office, ''Titles and Designations of Formations and Units of the Territorial Army'', London, 7 November 1927.\n* Ray Westlake, ''Tracing the Rifle Volunteers 1859-1908: A Guide for Military and Family Historians'', [[Barnsley]], UK: Pen & Sword Military, 2010, {{ISBN|9781844686940}}.\n* Ray Westlake, ''The Territorials 1908-1914: A Guide for Military and Family Historians'', Barnsley, UK: Pen & Sword Military, 2011, {{ISBN|978-1-84884-360-8}}.\n* Everard Wyrall, ''The Fiftieth Division 1914\u20131919'', 1939/Uckfield: Naval & Military, nd, {{ISBN|1-84342-206-9}}.\n{{refend}}\n==External sources==\n* [http://british-army-units1945on.co.uk British Army units from 1945 on]\n* [https://www.forces-war-records.co.uk Forces War Records]\n* [http://www.gracesguide.co.uk/Main_Page Grace's Guide to British Industrial History]\n* [http://www.geograph.org.uk Great War Centenary Drill Halls]\n* [http://www.longlongtrail.co.uk The Long, Long Trail]\n* [http://www.patriotfiles.com/index.php?name=Sections&req=listarticles&secid=17 Orders of Battle at Patriot Files]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051228103659/http://www.regiments.org/regiments/index.htm T.F. Mills, Land Forces of Britain, the Empire and Commonwealth \u2013 Regiments.org (archive site)]\n* [http://www.orbat.info/history/historical/uk/ta47.html Graham Watson, ''The Territorial Army 1947'']\n\n[[Category:Royal Northumberland Fusiliers]]\n[[Category:Infantry battalions of the British Army]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations in Northumberland]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations in Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1861]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1920]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1947]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1918]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1945]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1950]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name = 2nd Northumberland Rifle Volunteer Corps<br>5th Bn, Royal Northumberland Fusiliers<br>53rd (Royal Northumberland Fusiliers) S/L Rgt, RA<br>638th (Royal Northumberland Fusiliers) Rgt, RA<br>588 (Royal Northumberland Fusiliers) LAA Rgt,RA\n| image = Royal_Northumberland_Fusiliers_Cap_Badge.jpg\n| caption = [[Royal Northumberland Fusiliers]] cap badge\n| dates = 1861\u20141918<br>1920\u20141945<br>1947\u20141950\n| country = {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n| allegiance = \n| branch = {{army|United Kingdom}}\n*[[Royal Northumberland Fusiliers]]\n*[[Royal Artillery]]\n| type = [[Infantry]]<br>[[Searchlight]]<br>Light Anti-Aircraft Artillery\n| role = Air defence artillery\n| size = [[Battalion]]/[[Regiment]]\n| command_structure = \n| garrison = [[Walker-on-Tyne]]\n| nickname = Tynemouth Rifles\n| patron = \n| motto = \n| colors = \n| march = \n| mascot = \n| battles = [[Second Boer War|South African War]]<br>[[World War I]]<br>[[World War II]]\n| anniversaries = \n| current_commander = \n| ceremonial_chief = \n| colonel_of_the_regiment = \n| notable_commanders = \n}}{{Short description|The 2nd Northumberland RVC, later 5th Btn, Royal Northumberland Fus was a reserve army unit of the [[British Army]] which saw service during the world wars.}}\nThe '''2nd Northumberland Rifle Volunteer Corps''', also referred to as the Tynemouth Rifles, was an infantry unit of Britain's part-time force, the [[Territorial Army (United Kingdom)|Territorial Army]]. The corps was raised during the expansion of the [[Volunteer Force|Volunteer movement]] in the 1850s and then served with the [[Territorial Force]] during [[World War I]]. It converted to an anti-aircraft role just prior to [[World War II]], and continued to serve until it was amalgamated in 1950.\n\n== Volunteer Force ==\nThe enthusiasm for the Volunteer movement following an invasion scare in 1859 saw the creation of many Rifle Volunteer Corps (RVCs) composed of part-time soldiers eager to supplement the Regular [[British Army]] in time of need.<ref>Beckett.</ref><ref>Westlake, ''Rifle Volunteers''.</ref> One of these new corps was the 1st Northumberland RVC (also known as the Northumberland Rifles) formed in [[North Shields]] and [[Tynemouth]] on 16 August 1859 by coal-owner Edward Potter of [[Cramlington]]. It took some moral courage to appear in the street in Volunteer uniform: members of the 1st Northumberland RVC were sneered at as 'noodles'. However, the movement continued to grow: in February 1860 the 1st absorbed the 2nd Northumberland RVC of three companies, also formed at Tynemouth on 4 January that year. In August 1861 it split to form the 1st (Tynemouth), 8th (three companies at [[Walker-on-Tyne]]) and 9th (Cramlington) Northumberland RVCs, which were all placed in the '''2nd Administrative Battalion of Northumberland Rifle Volunteers'''. The 1st disbanded in October 1862 and the 9th in December 1864, but the '''8th (Walker) Northumberland RVC''' thrived. The HQ of the 2nd Admin Battalion moved to Walker after the disbandment of the 1st; it was disbanded in 1865 and the 8th continued as an independent corps with James Anderson, a former [[Ensign_(rank)#United_Kingdom|ensign]] in the [[30th Foot]], as [[Lieutenant colonel (United Kingdom)|lieutenant-colonel]] in command. A number of its officers were drawn from the prominent Tyneside family of Swan.<ref name=\":12\">Westlake, ''Rifle Volunteers'', pp. 191\u20133.</ref><ref>Beckett, pp. 63, 96 and Appendix VII.</ref><ref name = List>''Army List''.</ref><ref name=\":02\">Frederick, Volume I, pp. 276-7.</ref><ref name=\":22\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20071021105818/http://www.regiments.org/regiments/uk/volmil-england/vinf-no/nd-5.htm 5th Battalion, The Royal Northumberland Fusiliers at Regiments.org, retrieved 15 February 2020.]</ref><ref>Beckett, p. 63; Appendix VII.</ref> During this period, the battalion was organised as;<ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":22\" />\n\n* Battalion Headquarters in [[Tynemouth]] ''\u2013 HQ moving to [[Newcastle upon Tyne]] in 1863''\n* 1st (Tynemouth) Northumberland RVC \u2013 ''raised 16 August 1859: three coys separated Aug 1861 to form 8th RVC in Walker and one coy separated to form 9th RVC in [[Cramlington]]: disbanded Oct 1862''\n* 8th (Walker) Northumberland RVC \u2013 ''formed Aug 1861 from three coys of the 1st RVC''\n* 9th (Cramlington) Northumberland RVC \u2013 ''formed Aug 1861 from one coy of 1st RVC: disbanded Dec 1864''\n\nUnder the scheme of 'localisation' introduced by the [[Cardwell Reforms]] in 1873, the Northumberland and [[Newcastle upon Tyne]] RVCs, together with the two Regular battalions of the Northumberland Fusiliers and the [[Militia and Volunteers of Northumberland|Northumberland Militia]], constituted Brigade No 1, based at Newcastle in the County of Northumberland sub-district of [[Northern Command (United Kingdom)|Northern District]]. While the sub-districts were referred to as 'brigades', they were purely administrative organisations and the Volunteers were excluded from the 'mobilisation' part of the Cardwell system, though they carried out joint manoeuvres.<ref name = List/><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20051230125426/http://www.regiments.org/regiments/uk/depot/1873.htm Training Depots, 1873\u20131881 at Regiments.org.]</ref> Lieutenant-Colonel Anderson retired in 1875 and was appointed [[Colonel_(United_Kingdom)#Honorary_Colonel|Honorary Colonel]] of the battalion; he was succeeded in command by Henry Swan who ran the Walker shipyard of [[Charles Mitchell (shipbuilder)|Charles Mitchell]] and later [[Armstrong Whitworth]]. Swan remained in command until 1902.<ref name = List/><ref>[https://www.gracesguide.co.uk/Henry_Frederick_Swan Henry Frederick Swan at Grace's Guides.]</ref>\n\nWhen the RVCs were consolidated nationwide on 3 September 1880, the 8th RVC was re-numbered as the '''2nd Northumberland Rifle Volunteer Corps''' with companies designated as 'A' to 'F'.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":22\" /> After the [[Childers Reforms]] the RVCs became Volunteer Battalions of their affiliated Regular Army regiment and in 1883 the 2nd Northumberland RVC became the '''2nd Volunteer Battalion, Northumberland Fusiliers''' and  wore a scarlet coat with Gosling green [[Facing colour|facings]].<ref name=\":12\"/><ref name = List/> The [[Stanhope Memorandum]] of December 1888 proposed a more comprehensive Mobilisation Scheme for Volunteer units, which would assemble in their own brigades at key points in case of war. In peacetime these brigades provided a structure for collective training.<ref>Beckett, pp. 135, 185\u20136.</ref><ref>Dunlop, pp. 60\u20131.</ref> Under this scheme the 2nd and 3rd VBs of the Northumberland Fusiliers and the five [[Durham Light Infantry]] VBs formed the Tyne and Tees Brigade.<ref name = List/>\n\nIn 1894, K Company from the 1st Volunteer Battalion at [[Newburn]] (formed in 1885) was transferred to the 2nd as G Company. The following year the 2nd VB formed a new company at [[Wallsend]] and by 1900 the battalion had grown to ten companies, at Walker (4), Newburn (2), Wallsend (2) and [[Gosforth]] (2).<ref name=\":12\"/>\n\nBetween 1900\u201302, volunteers from the 2nd VB went to [[South Africa]] and participated with their Regular counterparts in the 1st and 2nd Battalions.  As a reward for their service, the battalion was granted its first battle honour: ''South Africa 1900-02'''''.'''  Engagements during this period included service in the [[Orange Free State]], service in [[Transvaal Colony|Transvaal]], and later the [[Battle of Rustenburg]].<ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":32\">Westlake, ''Territorials'', p. 43.</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071023193049/http://regiments.org/wars/19thcent/99za-abw.htm  Second Anglo-Boer War 1899-1902 at Regiments.org, retrieved 16 February 2020.]</ref>\n\n== Territorial Force ==\nIn 1907, [[Secretary of State for War]] [[Richard Haldane, 1st Viscount Haldane|Richard Haldane]] announced a series of Army reforms, which would affect mostly the [[Volunteer Force|Volunteers]] and [[Imperial Yeomanry|Yeomanry]]. These two groups were merged to form the [[Territorial Force]] on 1 April 1908.  As part of these reforms, all of the volunteer battalions became numbered battalions of their patrent regiments. The battalion was renamed as the '''5th Battalion, The Northumberland Fusiliers''' and subsequently re-organised as follows:<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":32\" /><ref>Westlake, ''Territorials'', Introduction</ref><ref>[http://www.geograph.org.uk/article/WW1-Great-War-Centenary---Drill-Halls/8#northumberland Northumberland at Great War Centenary Drill Halls]. Retrieved 16 February 2020.</ref><ref name = List/><ref>Dunlop, Chapter 14.</ref><ref>[http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/28121/supplements/2153 ''London Gazette'' 20 March 1908.]</ref>\n* Battalion Headquarters in Walker\n* A\u2013C Companies in Walker\n* D\u2013F Companies in [[Wallsend]]\n* G Company in [[Gosforth]] with detachments in [[West Moor]] and [[Seaton Burn]]\n* H Company in Gosforth\n\nAnother organisational change of the reforms of 1908 was the creation in the TF of 14 divisions, 14 mounted brigades, and coastal defence troops. One of these new divisions was the [[Northumbrian Division]] (later the 50th), and in this division was the [[Northumbrian Brigade]] (later the [[149th (Northumberland) Brigade|149th]]). The 5th Bn along with the 4th, 6th, and 7th bns of the Royal Northumberland Fusiliers were all part of this brigade.<ref name = Becke50>Becke, Pt 2a, pp. 93\u2013100.</ref><ref name=\":42\">[http://www.longlongtrail.co.uk/army/order-of-battle-of-divisions/50th-northumbrian-division/ 50th (Northumbrian) Division at The Long, Long Trail, retrieved 16 February 2020.]</ref><ref name=\":52\">[http://www.longlongtrail.co.uk/army/regiments-and-corps/the-british-infantry-regiments-of-1914-1918/northumberland-fusiliers/ Northumberland Fusiliers at The Long, Long Trail, retrieved 16 February 2020]</ref>\n\n== World War I ==\n===Mobilisation===\nIn July of 1914, as the international situation worsened, the [[British Armed Forces]] were on high alert as the [[Imperial German Army]] moved towards the neutral nation of the [[Kingdom of Belgium]], of which the [[United Kingdom]] protected under the [[Treaty of London (1839)|Treaty of London]]. When German forces crossed into [[Belgium]], the [[United Kingdom]] declared war on [[Germany]] and later the rest of the [[Central Powers]]. At the time the units of the Northumbrian Division were at their annual training camp in [[North Wales]]. On 3 August they were ordered to return to their respective headquarters, where at 17.00 next day they received orders to [[Mobilization|mobilise]]. The units went to their war stations along the coast, where there were numerous alerts. In October the division became part of [[Central Force]] in Home Defence and manned the [[Tyne]] Defences.<ref name = Becke50/><ref name=\":52\"/><ref>Wyrall, p.4.</ref>\n\nOn the outbreak of war, TF units were invited to volunteer for Overseas Service. The large majority of the Northumbrian Division accepted. On 15 August the [[War Office]] (WO) issued instructions to separate those men who had signed up for Home Service only, and form these into reserve units. On 31 August, the formation of a reserve or 2nd Line unit was authorised for each 1st Line unit where 60 per cent or more of the men had volunteered for Overseas Service. The titles of these 2nd Line units would be the same as the original, but distinguished by a '2/' prefix. In this way duplicate battalions, brigades and divisions were created, mirroring those TF formations being sent overseas.<ref name = Becke63>Becke, Pt 2b, pp. 49\u201354.</ref><ref name = Trail63>[http://www.longlongtrail.co.uk/army/order-of-battle-of-divisions/63rd-2nd-northumbrian-division/ 63rd (2nd Northumbrian) Division at Long, Long Trail.]</ref><ref>Becke, Pt 2b, p. 6.</ref><ref>Wyrall, pp. 4\u20135.</ref>\n\n=== 1/5th Battalion ===\n[[File:Northumberland Fusiliers at Thiepval Sept 1916 IWM Q 1349.jpg|thumb|Northumberland Fusiliers in a reserve trench at [[Thiepval]], September 1916.]]\nIn  April 1915 the 1/5th Battalion moved to [[France]] and saw action during some notable battles including:<ref name=\":42\" /><ref name=\":52\" /><ref name=\":0\">[https://www.forces-war-records.co.uk/units/217/royal-northumberland-fusiliers Unit History: Royal Northumberland Fusiliers at Forces War Records, retrieved 16 February 2020.]</ref><ref>Wyrall.</ref>\n* 1915: [[Battle of St Julien]], [[Battle of Frezenberg|Battle of Frezenburg]], and [[Battle of Bellewaarde|Battle of Bellewaarde Ridge]]\n* 1916: [[Battle of Flers-Courcelette]], [[Battle of Morval]], and [[Battle of Le Transloy|Battle of the Transloy Ridges]]\n* 1917: [[Battle of Arras (1917)|First Battle of the Scarpe]], Capture of [[Wancourt]] Ridge, [[Second Battle of the Scarpe]], and [[Second Battle of Passchendaele]]\n* 1918: [[Battle of St Quentin Canal|Battle of St Quentin]], [[Operation_Michael#Actions_at_the_Somme_crossings,_24\u201325_March|Actions at the Somme Crossings]], [[Battle of Rosieres]], [[Battle of Estaires]], [[Battle of Hazebrouck]], and [[Battle of the Aisne]]\n\nFollowing the armistice on 11 November 1918, the battalion was reduced to a [[Cadre (military)|cadre]] on 15 July and disembodied on 6 November 1918.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":42\" /><ref name=\":52\" />\n\n=== 2/5th Battalion ===\nThe 2/5th Battalion was formed in [[Blyth, Northumberland|Blyth]] along with the 2/4th on the 22\u201323 November 1914 just before their respective first line battalions were preparing to go overseas.  This new battalion joined the [[188th (2/1st Northumberland) Brigade]] in the newly formed 2nd line [[63rd (2nd Northumbrian) Division]] in January 1915.  In July 1916 the division was divided, and the battalion became independent and eventually joined the [[217th Brigade (United Kingdom)|217th Brigade]] in the [[72nd Division (United Kingdom)|72nd Division]]. Finally, on 6 December 1918 the battalion was disbanded while stationed in [[Ipswich]] and replaced by the 264th (Infantry) Battalion, [[Training Reserve]].<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":52\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name = Becke63/><ref name = Trail63/>\n\n=== 5th (Reserve) Battalion ===\nThe '''3/5th Battalion''', later 5th (Reserve) Btn, was the last of the duplicates formed with the 3/4th, 3/6th, and 3/7th formed in June 1915.  On 8 April 1916 the battalions were all redesignated as 'reserve', and became the 5th (Reserve) Battalion.  On 1 September 1918 the battalion was absorbed into the 4th (Reserve) Battalion.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":52\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Interwar ==\nWhen the [[Territorial Force]] was disembodied after the end of [[World War I]], the army was left with just the regulars, most of which were under-strength or just at [[Cadre (military)|cadre]] size. On 7 February 1920 the TF and most of its units were reconstituted, including the 5th Battalion, The Northumberland Fusiliers at Walker-on-Tyne with 'A', 'B', 'C', and 'D' Companies. Once again it formed part of 149th (Northumberland) Brigade in 50th (Northumbrian) Division.<ref>''Titles and Designations'' 1927.</ref> In 1921 the TF was reorganised as the [[Territorial Army (United Kingdom)|Territorial Army]]. On 3 June 1935 as part of [[George V]]\u2019s silver jubilee celebrations the regiment was granted a Royal title along with three other Regiments and became the [[Royal Northumberland Fusiliers]], and the battalion was re-named likewise.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== 5th Battalion, Royal Northumberland Fusiliers (53rd Searchlight Regiment) ===\nIn the late 1930s the increasing need for anti-aircraft (AA) defence for Britain's cities was addressed by converting a number of TA infantry battalions into searchlight (S/L) units, which accelerated after the [[Munich Crisis]]. The 5th Battalion was one of those selected, and was converted on 1 November 1938 as '''5th Battalion, Royal Northumberland Fusiliers (53rd Searchlight Regiment)''', organised as follows:<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":2\">Frederick, p. 869.</ref><ref name=\":62\">The Monthly Army List, ''[https://deriv.nls.uk/dcn23/1055/2061/105520619.23.pdf August 1939] (pdf)'', [[London]]: His Majesty's Stationary Office (1939), Retrieved 16 February 2020.</ref>\n* Battalion Headquarters, Church Street Drill hall, [[Walker-on-Tyne]] under [[Lieutenant Colonel]] W H Leete, [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|DFC]], [[Territorial Decoration|TD]]\n* 408th S/L Company under [[Major]] G. M. I. Stanley\n* 409th S/L Company under [[Major]] F. H. Phillips\n* 410th S/L Company under [[Major]] A. E. B. Plummer, [[Military Cross|MC]]\n* Affiliation with Armstrong-Whitworth (Walker) Cadet Unit (placed under administrative command)\n\nUnlike some of the infantry battalions previously converted to the AA S/L role, which had transferred to the [[Royal Engineers]] (RE), the 5th Bn remained part of the Royal Northumberland Fusiliers for the time being.\n\nFollowing its change of role, the battalion was placed under the command of the [[30th (Northumbrian) Anti-Aircraft Brigade]]. This was subordinated to [[3rd Anti-Aircraft Division (United Kingdom)|3rd Anti-Aircraft Division]], but by the outbreak of war came under a newly-formed  [[7th Anti-Aircraft Division (United Kingdom)|7th AA Division]] tasked with covering  [[North East England]].<ref name = List/><ref name=\":3\">[http://www.patriotfiles.com/index.php?name=Sections&req=viewarticle&artid=6697&page=1 British Anti-Aircraft Command, TA on 3 September 1939] at the [http://www.patriotfiles.com Patriot Files]. Retrieved 16 February 2020.</ref><ref>Routledge, Table LX, p. 378.</ref><ref>Pettibone, p. 298.</ref>\n\n== World War II ==\n===Mobilisation===\nIn February 1939 the existing AA defences came under the control of a new [[Anti-Aircraft Command]]. In June, as the international situation worsened, a partial mobilisation of the TA was begun in a process known as 'couverture', whereby each AA unit did a month's tour of duty in rotation to man selected AA gun and S/L positions. On 24 August, ahead of the declaration of war, AA Command was fully mobilised at its war stations. The 5th Battalion was deployed to support the Newcastle Gun Defence Area (GDA). The S/L layouts had been planned on a spacing of {{convert|3500|yd|m}}, but due to equipment shortages this was extended to {{convert|6000|yd|m}}.<ref>Routledge, pp. 388-9.</ref><ref>Routledge, pp. 65\u20136, 371, 388-9; Table LIX, p. 377.</ref>\n\nOn 1 August 1940 all of the RE and infantry AA units were brought under command of the [[Royal Artillery]]. Therefore the battalion was re-named as the '''53rd (Royal Northumberland Fusiliers) Searchlight Regiment, Royal Artillery''' with its companies (408, 409, and 410) becoming batteries.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":1\">Litchfield, p. 195.</ref><ref>[http://www.ra39-45.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/sl/page33.html 53 (R Northumberland Fus) Searchlight Regt RA (TA)] at [http://www.ra39-45.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk Royal Artillery 1939-45], [https://web.archive.org/web/20090107170758/http://www.ra39-45.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/sl/page33.html Archived] on 7 January 2009 at the [https://web.archive.org Wayback Machine]. Retrieved 16 February 2020.</ref><ref name = FarnM>Farndale, Annex M.</ref> During this re-organisation, [[Anti-Aircraft Command]] (AA Command) was also being overhauled, with many new brigades and divisions being formed, one of them being the [[57th Light Anti-Aircraft Brigade (United Kingdom)|57th Light Anti-Aircraft Brigade]] formed on 25 August 1939 which initially only controlled the Light AA (LAA) units of the division.<ref>David A. Ryan, Dr. Graham Watson, and Robert Michel, [http://niehorster.org/017_britain/39_commands/aa-07.html 7th Anti-Aircraft Division, Anti-Aircraft Command] at [http://niehorster.org World War II Armed Forces - Orders of Battle and Organizations]. Retrieved 16 February 2020.</ref><ref>Frederick, p. 1050.</ref><ref>[http://www.ra39-45.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/home/page54.html 7 AA Division] at [http://www.ra39-45.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk Royal Artillery 1939-45], [https://web.archive.org/web/20140224020652/http://www.ra39-45.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/home/page54.html Archived] on 24 February 2014 at the [https://web.archive.orgo.uk/home/page54.html Wayback Machine]. Retrieved 16 February 2020.</ref>\n[[File:The British Army in the United Kingdom 1939-45 H35912.jpg|thumb|150 cm Anti-aircraft searchlight equipped with SLC (AA Radar No 2) during World War II.]]\n===Newcastle Blitz===\nDuring the ''[[Luftwaffe]]'' night-bombing campaign against British cities in the winter of 1940\u201341 ([[The Blitz]]) 30 AA Bde controlled the AA guns in the Newcastle GDA, while 57 AA Bde controlled the S/L layout, including 53rd S/L Regiment. The regiment served through the [[Newcastle Blitz]].<ref>Routledge, Table LXV, p. 397.</ref><ref>Farndale, Annex D.</ref><ref name = Orbat79>Order of Battle of Non-Field Force Units in the United Kingdom, Part 27: AA Command, 12 May 1941, with amendments, [[The National Archives (United Kingdom)|The National Archives (TNA), Kew]], file WO 212/79.</ref> In November 1940 AA Command changed its S/L layouts to clusters of three lights to improve illumination, but this meant that the clusters had to be spaced {{convert|10400|yd|m}} apart. The cluster system was an attempt to improve the chances of picking up enemy bombers and keeping them illuminated for engagement by AA guns or [[Royal Air Force]] (RAF) [[Night fighter]]s. Eventually, one light in each cluster was to be equipped with [[Searchlight Control radar]] (SLC) and act as 'master light', but the radar equipment was still in short supply.<ref>Routledge, p. 393.</ref><ref>Farndale, p. 107.</ref>\n\nOn 17 April 1941, 565 S/L Bty was formed under the [[236th Searchlight Training Regiment, Royal Artillery|236th Searchlight Training Rgt]] at [[Oswestry]] from a [[Cadre (military)|cadre]] provided by 53rd S/L Regiment, and shortly joined, and regimented on 12 August 1941.  On 18 February 1942, the regiment had a small name change, to become the '''53rd Searchlight Regiment, Royal Artillery (Royal Northumberland Fusiliers)'''.<ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":4\">Frederick, Volume II, p. 862.</ref><ref>Frederick, Volume II, p. 869.</ref>\n\nBy December 1941 the regiment had moved to [[43rd Anti-Aircraft Brigade (United Kingdom)|43 AA Bde]], still in 7th AA Division but now deployed covering [[Wearside]] and [[Teesside]].<ref>Order of Battle of Non-Field Force Units in the United Kingdom, Part 27: AA Command, 2 December 1941, TNA file WO 212/80.</ref> It remained under 43 AA Bde until August 1942 when it returned to 30 AA Bde<ref> Order of Battle of Non-Field Force Units in the United Kingdom, Part 27: AA Command, 14 May 1942, with amendments, TNA file WO 212/81.</ref><ref>Order of Battle of Non-Field Force Units in the United Kingdom, Part 27: AA Command, 1 October 1942, TNA file WO 212/82.</ref><ref>Order of Battle of Non-Field Force Units in the United Kingdom, Part 27: AA Command, 13 March 1943, TNA file WO 212/83.</ref><ref> Order of Battle of AA Command, 1 August 1943, TNA file WO 212/84.</ref>\n\n===Operation Diver===\nBy  late 1943, AA Command was being forced to release manpower for overseas service, particularly [[Operation Overlord]] (the planned Allied invasion of Normandy) and most S/L regiments lost one of their four batteries. 565 S/L Battery began to disband on 25 February 1944, which it completed by 24 March.<ref name=\":22\" /><ref name = Rout408>Routledge, pp. 408\u201310.</ref> In March 1944, 30 AA Bde HQ was transferred to the south of England; 53rd S/L Rgt also went south, but joined [[47th Anti-Aircraft Brigade (United Kingdom)|47 AA Bde]] in [[2nd Anti-Aircraft Group (United Kingdom)|2 AA Group]]. 2 AA Group was responsible for defending the 'Overlord' assembly camps, depots and embarkation ports and was planning for the expected onslaught of [[V-1 flying bomb]]s against London. Meanwhile, the group had to deal with a sharp increase in ''Luftwaffe'' air raids trying to reach London, which continued until May.<ref name = Pile>[https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/38149/page/5973 Pile.]</ref><ref name = Rout408/><ref>Order of Battle of AA Command, 27 April 1944, TNA file WO 212/85.</ref>\n\nOn 13 June, a week after the Overlord fleets had left to launch [[D Day]], the first V-1s appeared over southern England. 2 AA Group deployed its Light AA guns alongside S/L positions, hoping that the SLC could guide the LAA guns at night. By day, the S/L positions used their AA [[Light machine guns]] in an effort to bring down the fast-moving missiles. The early success rate was low, but later fighter aircraft and radar-directed Heavy AA guns achieved high rates of success against V-1s.<ref name = Pile/><ref name = Rout408/>  \n\n===638th (Royal Northumberland Fusiliers) Infantry Regiment, RA===\nIn January 1945, the diminishing threat of the [[Luftwaffe]] coupled with a manpower shortage in [[21st Army Group]], particularly in the infantry, led to the conversion of surplus anti-aircraft and coastal artillery regiments in the UK into infantry units. 53rd Searchlight Regiment was one of the regiments selected but it did not revert to its original title, instead becoming '''638th (Royal Northumberland Fusiliers) Regiment, Royal Artillery''' on 23 January 1945.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name = FarnM/><ref name=\":5\">Frederick, Volume II, p. 883.</ref><ref>[http://www.ra39-45.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/infantry/page38.html 638 (R Northumberland Fus) Regt RA (TA)] at [http://www.ra39-45.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk Royal Artillery 1939-45], [https://web.archive.org/web/20090107112151/http://www.ra39-45.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/infantry/page38.html Archived] on 7 January 2009 at the [https://web.archive.org Wayback Machine]. Retrieved 16 February 2020.</ref>\n\nThe regiment was attached to [[38th Light Anti-Aircraft Brigade (United Kingdom)|38 AA Bde]], which was converting into [[304th Infantry Brigade (United Kingdom)|304 Infantry Brigade]]. After infantry training, including a short period attached to [[55th (West Lancashire) Infantry Division]], the brigade was moved into the [[War Office]] Reserve, and shipped to [[Norway]], landing on 7 June 1945 and joining [[Norway Command]] following the liberation of that country ([[Operation Doomsday]]).<ref>Joslen, p. 400.</ref> The regiment was still in Norway on 15 November 1945 when 638 Rgt began the process of entering suspended animation, completing the process on 13 December.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Postwar ==\nFollowing the end of hostilities most territorial artillery regiments had been placed in suspended animation by late 1946. On 1 January 1947 most of these regiments were reconstituted and many new regiments were formed as part of the reformed and re-organised TA, with new numbers according to the renumbering plan for the complete re-designation of all RA units, both regular and territorial.  In accordance with this, the light anti-aircraft (LAA) regiments were assigned numbers between 512 and 588. The 5th Btn was reformed as '''588th (Royal Northumberland Fusiliers) Light Anti-Aircraft Regiment, Royal Artillery''', and followed the new standard RA organisation, which consisted of RHQ, P, Q, and R Batteries, all of which were based in Walker on Tyne. The regiment provided the LAA component of the TA's [[50th (Northumbrian) Infantry Division]].<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name = FarnM/><ref name=\":6\">Litchfield, pp. 5-6.</ref><ref>Frederick, Volume II, p. 1024.</ref><ref>[http://www.orbat.info/history/historical/uk/ta47.html  Watson, ''TA 1947''.]</ref><ref>Litchfield, Appendix 5.</ref><ref name = 45on>[http://british-army-units1945on.co.uk/territorial-army-royal-artillery/564-591-regiments.html 564\u2013591 Rgts RA at British Army 1945 on.]</ref>\n\nOn 1 September 1950 the regiment was converted back to infantry and simultaneously merged with the 4th Btn to form the '''4th/5th Battalion, The Royal Northumberland Fusiliers'''.  In 1967 the battalion's [[Territorial and Army Volunteer Reserve]] (TAVR) successors were A (Royal Northumberland Fusiliers) Company, [[Fusilier Volunteers]] and the 4th/5th/6th (Territorial) Battalion, [[Royal Northumberland Fusiliers]] both of which were eventually expanded into the [[6th (Northumberland) Battalion, The Royal Regiment of Fusiliers]].  The Northumberland TA successors are currently part of 'X' and 'Z' companies in the [[5th (Volunteer) Battalion, The Royal Regiment of Fusiliers]].<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":6\" /><ref name = 45on/><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20060117220814/http://www.regiments.org:80/regiments/uk/volmil-england/vinf-no/nd-4.htm 4/5th Bn Northumberland Fusiliers at Regiments.org.]</ref><ref>[https://www.britishbadgeforum.com/forums/attachment.php?attachmentid=106964&d=1401909298 New Title for Reserve Army Units]; [https://www.britishbadgeforum.com/forums/attachment.php?attachmentid=106965&d=1401909330 T&AVR Category II: The Volunteers], The Territorial Magazine, April 1967. Retrieved 16 February 2020.</ref><ref>[https://www.britishbadgeforum.com/forums/attachment.php?attachmentid=106964&d=1401909298 New Title for Reserve Army Units]; [https://www.britishbadgeforum.com/forums/attachment.php?attachmentid=106969&d=1401909545 T&AVR Category III: The Territorials], The Territorial Magazine, April 1967. Retrieved 16 February 2020.</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071020113534/http://www.regiments.org/regiments/uk/volmil-england/vinf-no/nd-4.htm 4th Battalion, The Royal Northumberland Fusiliers at Regiments.org,  retrieved 16 February 2020.]</ref><ref>[http://www.orbat.info/history/historical/uk/ta47.html Watson, ''TA 1947'', retrieved 16 February 2020.]</ref><ref>Wienand Drenth, ''[https://www.orbat85.nl/documents/The%20Territorial%20Army%201967-2000.pdf The Territorial Army 1967-2000] (pdf)'', 2000: [[Eindhoven]], [[Kingdom of the Netherlands]].</ref><ref>[https://www.army.mod.uk/who-we-are/corps-regiments-and-units/infantry/royal-regiment-of-fusiliers/ The Royal Regiment of Fusiliers], [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]], [[London]].</ref>\n\n== Personalities ==\n'''Commanding Officers'''\n\nThose commanding officers which served during [[World War I]]:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ww1infantrycos.co.uk/northumberland.html|title=First World War Infantry Battalion Commanding Officers - Page 13|website=www.ww1infantrycos.co.uk|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\n''1/5th Battalion''\n\n* [[Lieutenant Colonel]] David Ross MacDonald, 4 August 1914 > replaced\n* [[Colonel]] Arthur Horsman Coles, 25 November 1915 > replaced\n* [[Lieutenant Colonel]] Hermann Luhrs, 26 November 1915 > replaced\n* [[Lieutenant Colonel]] Francis Charles Turner, 14 March 1916 > replaced\n* [[Lieutenant Colonel]] Nicholas Irwin Wright, 27 September 1916 > invalided\n* [[Lieutenant Colonel]] Arnold Irwin, 17 March 1918 > wounded\n* [[Lieutenant Colonel]] Ivan Marshall Tweedy 1 May 1918 > replaced\n* [[Lieutenant Colonel]] Henry Robert Brown 13 July 1918 > remained CO\n\n''2/5th Battalion''\n\n* [[Lieutenant Colonel]] David Ross MacDonald, 25 November 1914 > replaced\n* [[Lieutenant Colonel]] Francis William Iles 28 August 1915 > replaced\n* [[Lieutenant Colonel]] Lionel Grant Oliver, 16 May 1916 > replaced\n\n''3/5th (5th Reserve) Battalion''\n\n* [[Lieutenant Colonel]] Thomas Joseph Carlile, 15 June 1915 > replaced\n\n'''Honorary Colonels'''\n\nThe battalion's (later regiment's) [[Colonel_(United_Kingdom)#Honorary_Colonel|Honorary Colonels]] included:<ref name = List/><ref name=\":22\" />\n* 1875\u20131900, [[Colonel_(United_Kingdom)|Colonel]] James Anderson, former CO\n* 1900\u20131902, Vacant\n* 1902\u20131908, [[Brevet (military)|Brevet]] Colonel Henry Frederick Swan, [[Companions of the Order of the Bath|CB]], [[Volunteer Officers' Decoration|VD]]\n* 1908\u20131910, Vacant\n* 1910\u20131916, [[Lieutenant colonel (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant-Colonel]] [[Matthew White Ridley, 2nd Viscount Ridley]], [[Northumberland Hussars]]\n* 1916\u20131928, Vacant\n* 1928\u20131938, Honorary [[Brigadier General]] Hubert Horatio Shirley Morant, [[Distinguished Service Order|DSO]]\n* 1938\u20131950, Colonel Bernard Peatfield, [[OBE]], [[Military Cross|MC]], [[Territorial Decoration|TD]], DL (continued 1950 into 4th/5th Btn)\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n== References ==\n{{refbegin|2}}\n* Maj A.F. Becke,''History of the Great War: Order of Battle of Divisions, Part 2a: The Territorial Force Mounted Divisions and the 1st-Line Territorial Force Divisions (42\u201356)'', London: HM Stationery Office, 1935/Uckfield: Naval & Military Press, 2007, {{ISBN|1-847347-39-8}}.\n* Maj A.F. Becke,''History of the Great War: Order of Battle of Divisions, Part 2b: The 2nd-Line Territorial Force Divisions (57th\u201369th), with the Home-Service Divisions (71st\u201373rd) and 74th and 75th Divisions,'' London: HM Stationery Office, 1937/Uckfield: Naval & Military Press, 2007, {{ISBN|1-847347-39-8}}.\n* Ian F.W. Beckett, ''Riflemen Form: A Study of the Rifle Volunteer Movement 1859\u20131908'', Aldershot: Ogilby Trusts, 1982, {{ISBN|0 85936 271 X}}.\n* Col John K. Dunlop, ''The Development of the British Army 1899\u20131914'', London: Methuen, 1938.\n* Gen Sir [[Martin Farndale]], ''History of the Royal Regiment of Artillery: The Years of Defeat: Europe and North Africa, 1939\u20131941'', [[Woolwich]], UK: Royal Artillery Institution, 1988/[[London]], UK: Brasseys, 1996, {{ISBN|1-85753-080-2}}.\n* J.B.M. Frederick, ''Lineage Book of British Land Forces 1660-1978'', Volume I,  [[Wakefield]], UK: Microform Academic Publishers, 1984, {{ISBN|1-85117-007-3}}.\n* J.B.M. Frederick, ''Lineage Book of British Land Forces 1660-1978'', Volume II, Wakefield, UK: Microform Academic Publishers, 1984 {{ISBN|1-85117-008-1}}.\n* Lt-Col H.F. Joslen, ''Orders of Battle, Second World War, 1939\u20131945''. London, UK:  Her Majesty's Stationery Office, 1960/London Stamp Exchange, 1990, {{ISBN|0-948130-03-2}}/Uckfield, UK: Naval & Military Press, 2003, {{ISBN|1-843424-74-6}}.\n* Norman E. H. Litchfield, ''The Territorial Artillery 1908 - 