{"title_page": "List of British monarchs", "text_new": "{{original research|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|List of monarchs of Great Britain}}\n{{Redirect|British monarchs|ancient British monarchs|King of the Britons|legendary ones|List of legendary kings of Britain|those before 1707|List of English monarchs|and|List of Scottish monarchs|the current monarchy in general|Monarchy of the United Kingdom}}\n{{infobox\n| style = width: auto;\n| above = [[Royal coat of arms of the United Kingdom]]\n| image = [[File:Royal Coat of Arms of the United Kingdom (Both Realms).svg|300px|alt=Royal Arms]]\n| below =  The Royal Arms since the accession of [[Queen Victoria]] in 1837, featuring the [[Royal Arms of England|arms of England]] in both the first and fourth quarters, [[Royal coat of arms of Scotland|Scotland]] in the second and [[Coat of arms of Ireland|Ireland]] in the third. In [[Scotland]] a separate version is used (shown right), whereby the Arms of Scotland take precedence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/MonarchUK/Symbols/Coatsofarms.aspx |title=Coats of arms |website=royal.gov.uk |accessdate=9 May 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090304201929/http://www.royal.gov.uk/MonarchUK/Symbols/Coatsofarms.aspx |archivedate=4 March 2009}}</ref>}}\nThere have been 12 monarchs of the [[Kingdom of Great Britain]] and the [[United Kingdom]] (see [[Monarchy of the United Kingdom]]) since the merger of the [[Kingdom of England]] and the [[Kingdom of Scotland]] on 1 May 1707. England and Scotland had been in [[personal union]] under the [[House of Stuart]] since 24 March 1603. \n\nOn 1 January 1801, Great Britain merged with the [[Kingdom of Ireland]] (also previously in personal union with Great Britain) to form the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland]]. After [[Irish Free State|most of Ireland]] [[Anglo-Irish Treaty|left the union]] on 6 December 1922, its name was amended on 12 April 1927 to the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland.\n\n==House of Stuart (1707\u20131714)==\n{{Main article|House of Stuart}}\nAnne had ruled England, Scotland, and Ireland since 8 March 1702, and so became Queen of Great Britain upon the Union of England and Scotland. Her total reign lasted for 12 years and 21 weeks.\n\n{{Nobility table header|arms=yes|extra column=Claim !! Ref.}}\n\n|-\n! class=noprint colspan=2 style=\"font-weight:normal\" | {{xref|Before the [[Acts of Union 1707]]|selfref=no}} {{arrow}}\n! class=noprint colspan=6 style=\"font-weight:normal\" | {{xref|See [[List of English monarchs]], [[List of Scottish monarchs]]}}\n|-\n| <big>[[Anne, Queen of Great Britain|'''Anne''']]</big><br />1 May 1707<br />{{ndash}}<br />1 August 1714<br />''({{age in years and days|1707|5|1|1714|8|1}})''\n| [[File:Dahl, Michael - Queen Anne - NPG 6187.jpg|100px]]\n| [[File:Royal Arms of Great Britain (1707-1714).svg|100px]]\n| 6 February 1665<br />[[St James's Palace]]<hr />Daughter of [[James II and VII]]<br/>and [[Anne Hyde]]\n| [[Prince George of Denmark]]<br />[[St James's Palace]]<br />28 July 1683<br />No surviving children\n| 1 August 1714<br />[[Kensington Palace]]<br />Age: {{ayd|1665|2|6|1714|8|1}}\n| Daughter of [[James II and VII]]<hr />[[Cognatic primogeniture]]{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}<hr />[[Bill of Rights 1689]]\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royal.uk/anne-r-1702-1714|title=Anne (r. 1702\u20131714)|website=royal.gov.uk|accessdate=16 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180125020033/https://www.royal.uk/anne-r-1702-1714|archive-date=25 January 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n|}\n\n==House of Hanover (1714\u20131901)==\n{{Main article|House of Hanover}}\nThe Hanoverian succession came about as a result of the [[Act of Settlement 1701]], passed by the [[Parliament of England]], which excluded \"[[Papist]]s\" (i.e. Roman Catholics) from the succession. In return for access to the [[English overseas possessions|English plantations in North America and the West Indies]], the Hanoverian succession and the Union were ratified by the [[Parliament of Scotland]] in 1707.\n\nAfter the death of Anne, with no living children, her second cousin, George Louis, was the closest heir to the throne who was not Catholic. George was the son of [[Sophia of Hanover]]\u2014granddaughter of [[James VI and I]] through his daughter [[Elizabeth Stuart, Queen of Bohemia|Elizabeth]].{{efn-lr|For a family tree showing King George I's relationship to Queen Anne, see {{Slink|George I of Great Britain|Family tree}}.}}  The Hanoverian kings of Great Britain retained their German titles, first as [[Elector of Hanover|electors of Hanover]]/[[Duchy of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|dukes of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg]] and later as [[King of Hanover|kings of Hanover]]; the two lands were ruled as separate states in personal union.  The Hanoverian lands were separated when [[Queen Victoria]] ascended the throne of Great Britain; as German succession law prevented women from inheriting the Hanoverian throne, her uncle [[Ernest Augustus, King of Hanover|Ernest Augustus]] inherited in her stead.\n\n{{Nobility table header|arms=yes|extra column=Claim !! Ref.}}\n\n|-\n| <big>[[George I of Great Britain|{{nowrap|'''George I'''}}]]</big><br />'''George Louis'''<br />1 August 1714{{efn|King George I was crowned on 20 October 1714.}}<br />{{ndash}}<br />11 June 1727<br />''({{ayd|1714|8|1|1727|6|11|duration=yes}})''\n| [[File:King George I by Sir Godfrey Kneller, Bt.jpg|100px]]\n| [[File:Royal Arms of Great Britain (1714-1801).svg|100px]]\n| 28 May 1660<br />[[Leineschloss]]<hr />Son of [[Ernest Augustus, Elector of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|Ernest Augustus of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg]]<br />and [[Sophia of Hanover]]\n| [[Sophia Dorothea of Celle|Sophia Dorothea of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg-Celle]]<br />21 November 1682<br />2 children\n| 11 June 1727<br />[[Osnabr\u00fcck]]<br />Age: {{ayd|1660|5|28|1727|6|27}}\n| Great-grandson of {{nowrap|[[James VI and I]]}}<hr />Act of Settlement<hr />Eldest son of [[Sophia of Hanover]]\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royal.uk/george-i-r-1714-1727|title=George I (r. 1714\u20131727)|website=royal.gov.uk|accessdate=12 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160507210904/https://www.royal.uk/george-i-r-1714-1727|archive-date=7 May 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n|-\n| <big>[[George II of Great Britain|{{nowrap|'''George II'''}}]]</big><br />'''George Augustus'''<br />11 June 1727{{efn|King George II was crowned on 11 October 1727 with [[Caroline of Ansbach|Queen Caroline]].}}{{efn|Dates of start of reign and coronation given in [[Old Style]] calendar; date of death in New Style. (Duration of reign takes this into account.)}}<br />{{ndash}}<br />25 October 1760<br />''({{age in years and days|1727|6|22|1760|10|25|duration=yes}})''\n| [[File:George II by Thomas Hudson.jpg|100px]]\n| [[File:Royal Arms of Great Britain (1714-1801).svg|100px]]\n| 30 October 1683<br />[[Herrenhausen]]<hr />Son of [[George I of Great Britain|{{nowrap|George I}}]]<br />and [[Sophia Dorothea of Celle|Sophia Dorothea of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg-Celle]]\n| [[Caroline of Ansbach|Caroline of Brandenburg-Ansbach]]<br />22 August 1705<br />[[Herrenhausen]]<br />8 children\n| 25 October 1760<br />[[Kensington Palace]]<br />Age: {{ayd|1683|10|30|1760|10|25}}\n| Son of [[George I of Great Britain|{{nowrap|George I}}]]\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royal.uk/george-ii-r-1727-1760|title=George II (r. 1727\u20131760)|website=royal.gov.uk|accessdate=12 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160507222248/https://www.royal.uk/george-ii-r-1727-1760|archive-date=7 May 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n|-\n| <big>[[George III of the United Kingdom|{{nowrap|'''George III'''}}]]</big><br />'''George William Frederick'''<br />25 October 1760{{efn|King George III was crowned on 22 September 1761 with [[Queen Charlotte]].}}<br />{{ndash}}<br />29 January 1820<br />''({{age in years and days|1760|10|25|1820|1|29|duration=yes}})''\n| [[File:Allan Ramsay - King George III in coronation robes - Google Art Project.jpg|100px]]\n| [[File:Royal Arms of United Kingdom (1816-1837).svg|100px]]\n| 4 June 1738<br />[[Norfolk House]]<hr />Son of [[Frederick, Prince of Wales|Prince Frederick]]<br />and [[Princess Augusta of Saxe-Gotha|Augusta of Saxe-Gotha]]\n| [[Charlotte of Mecklenburg-Strelitz]]<br />[[St James's Palace]]<br />8 September 1761<br />15 children\n| 29 January 1820<br />[[Windsor Castle]]<br />Age: {{ayd|1738|6|4|1820|1|29}}\n| Grandson of [[George II of Great Britain|{{nowrap|George II}}]]\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royal.uk/george-iii-r-1760-1820|title=George III (r. 1760\u20131820)|website=royal.gov.uk|accessdate=12 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180520150812/https://www.royal.uk/george-iii-r-1760-1820|archive-date=20 May 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n|-\n| <big>[[George IV of the United Kingdom|{{nowrap|'''George IV'''}}]]</big><br />'''George Augustus Frederick'''<br />29 January 1820{{efn|King George IV was crowned on 19 July 1821.}}<br />{{ndash}}<br />26 June 1830<br />''({{age in years and days|1820|1|29|1830|6|26|duration=yes}})''\n| [[File:George IV 1821 color.jpg|100px]]\n| [[File:Royal Arms of United Kingdom (1816-1837).svg|100px]]\n| 12 August 1762<br />[[St James's Palace]]<hr />Son of [[George III of the United Kingdom|{{nowrap|George III}}]]<br />and [[Charlotte of Mecklenburg-Strelitz]]\n| {{grey|(1)}} [[Maria Fitzherbert]]<br />[[Park Lane]]<br />15 September 1785<br />No verified children<hr />{{grey|(2)}} [[Caroline of Brunswick|Caroline of Brunswick-Wolfenb\u00fcttel]]<br />St James's Palace<br />8 April 1795<br />1 daughter\n| 26 June 1830<br />Windsor Castle<br />Age: {{ayd|1762|8|12|1830|6|26}}\n| Son of [[George III of the United Kingdom|{{nowrap|George III}}]]\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royal.uk/king-george-iv-r-1820-1830|title=King George IV (r. 1820\u20131830)|website=royal.gov.uk|accessdate=12 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819063405/https://www.royal.uk/king-george-iv-r-1820-1830|archive-date=19 August 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n|-\n| <big>[[William IV of the United Kingdom|{{nowrap|'''William IV'''}}]]</big><br />'''William Henry'''<br />26 June 1830{{efn|King William IV was crowned on 8 September 1831 with [[Adelaide of Saxe-Meiningen|Queen Adelaide]].}}<br />{{ndash}}<br />20 June 1837<br />''({{age in years and days|1830|6|26|1837|6|20|duration=yes}})''\n| [[File:William IV.jpg|100px]]\n| [[File:Royal Arms of United Kingdom (1816-1837).svg|100px]]\n| 21 August 1765<br />[[Buckingham Palace]]<hr />Son of {{nowrap|George III}}<br />and Charlotte of Mecklenburg-Strelitz\n| [[Adelaide of Saxe-Meiningen]]<br />[[Kew Palace]]<br />13 July 1818<br />2 daughters\n| 20 June 1837<br />Windsor Castle<br />Age: {{ayd|1765|8|21|1837|6|20}}\n| Brother of [[George IV of the United Kingdom|{{nowrap|George IV}}]]\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royal.uk/william-iv-r-1830-1837|title=William IV (r. 1830\u20131837)|website=royal.gov.uk|accessdate=12 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170921001850/https://www.royal.uk/william-iv-r-1830-1837|archive-date=21 September 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n|-\n| <big>[[Queen Victoria|'''Victoria''']]</big><br />'''Alexandrina Victoria'''<br />20 June 1837{{efn|Queen Victoria was [[Coronation of Queen Victoria|crowned on 28 June 1838]].}}<br />{{ndash}}<br />22 January 1901<br />''({{age in years and days|1837|6|20|1901|1|22|duration=yes}})''\n| [[File:Queen Victoria 1843.jpg|100px]]\n| [[File:Arms of the United Kingdom (Variant 1).svg|100px]]\n| 24 May 1819<br />[[Kensington Palace]]<hr />Daughter of the [[Prince Edward, Duke of Kent and Strathearn|Duke of Kent and Strathearn]]<br />and [[Princess Victoria of Saxe-Coburg-Saalfeld|Victoria of Saxe-Coburg-Saalfeld]]\n| [[Albert, Prince Consort|Albert of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha]]<br />St James's Palace<br />[[Wedding of Queen Victoria and Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|10 February 1840]]<br />9 children\n| 22 January 1901<br />[[Osborne House]]<br />Age: {{ayd|1819|5|24|1901|1|22}}\n| Niece of [[William IV of the United Kingdom|{{nowrap|William IV}}]]\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royal.uk/victoria-r-1837-1901|title=Victoria ( r. 1837\u20131901)|website=royal.gov.uk|accessdate=12 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180125015954/https://www.royal.uk/victoria-r-1837-1901|archive-date=25 January 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n|}\n\n==House of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha (1901\u20131917)==\n{{main|House of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha}}\nBecause his father, [[Albert, Prince Consort]], was of the House of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha, Edward VII inaugurated a new royal house when he succeeded his mother, Victoria, the last monarch of the House of Hanover, in 1901.\n{{Nobility table header|arms=yes|extra column=Claim !! Ref.}}\n|-\n| <big>'''{{nowrap|[[Edward VII]]}}'''</big><br />'''Albert Edward'''<br />22 January 1901{{efn|King Edward VII was [[Coronation of King Edward VII and Queen Alexandra|crowned on 9 August 1902]] with [[Queen Alexandra]].}}<br />{{ndash}}<br />6 May 1910<br />''({{age in years and days|1901|1|22|1910|5|6|duration=yes}})''\n| [[File:King Edward VII by Sir (Samuel) Luke Fildes.jpg|100px]]\n| [[File:Arms of the United Kingdom (Variant 1).svg|100px]]\n| 9 November 1841<br />[[Buckingham Palace]]<hr />Son of [[Queen Victoria|Victoria]]<br />and [[Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha]]\n| [[Alexandra of Denmark]]<br />[[St George's Chapel, Windsor Castle|St George's Chapel]]<br />10 March 1863<br />6 children\n| 6 May 1910<br />[[Buckingham Palace]]<br />Age: {{ayd|1841|11|9|1910|5|6|}}\n| Son of [[Queen Victoria|Victoria]]\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royal.uk/edward-vii-r1901-1910|title=Edward VII (r.1901\u20131910)|website=royal.gov.uk|accessdate=12 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.