150206070811/http://britroyals.com/rulers.htm |archive-date=6 February 2015 |url-status=dead }}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.englishmonarchs.co.uk/ |title=English Monarchs \u2013 A complete history of the Kings and Queens of England |website=englishmonarchs.co.uk}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{British monarchs}}\n{{British royal titles}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:British Monarchs}}\n[[Category:British monarchy|*]]\n[[Category:British monarchy-related lists]]\n[[Category:Lists of monarchs]]\n[[Category:Lists of British monarchs]]\n", "text_old": "{{original research|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|List of monarchs of Great Britain}}\n{{Redirect|British monarchs|ancient British monarchs|King of the Britons|legendary ones|List of legendary kings of Britain|those before 1707|List of English monarchs|and|List of Scottish monarchs|the current monarchy in general|Monarchy of the United Kingdom}}\n{{infobox\n| style = width: auto;\n| above = [[Royal coat of arms of the United Kingdom]]\n| image = [[File:Royal Coat of Arms of the United Kingdom (Both Realms).svg|300px|alt=Royal Arms]]\n| below =  The Royal Arms since the accession of [[Queen Victoria]] in 1837, featuring the [[Royal Arms of England|arms of England]] in both the first and fourth quarters, [[Royal coat of arms of Scotland|Scotland]] in the second and [[Coat of arms of Ireland|Ireland]] in the third. In [[Scotland]] a separate version is used (shown right), whereby the Arms of Scotland take precedence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/MonarchUK/Symbols/Coatsofarms.aspx |title=Coats of arms |website=royal.gov.uk |accessdate=9 May 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090304201929/http://www.royal.gov.uk/MonarchUK/Symbols/Coatsofarms.aspx |archivedate=4 March 2009}}</ref>}}\nThere have been 12 monarchs of the [[Kingdom of Great Britain]] and the [[United Kingdom]] (see [[Monarchy of the United Kingdom]]) since the merger of the [[Kingdom of England]] and the [[Kingdom of Scotland]] on 1 May 1707. England and Scotland had been in [[personal union]] under the [[House of Stuart]] since 24 March 1603. \n\nOn 1 January 1801, Great Britain merged with the [[Kingdom of Ireland]] (also previously in personal union with Great Britain) to form the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland]]. After [[Irish Free State|most of Ireland]] [[Anglo-Irish Treaty|left the union]] on 6 December 1922, its name was amended on 12 April 1927 to the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland.\n\n==House of Stuart (1707\u20131714)==\n{{Main article|House of Stuart}}\nAnne had ruled England, Scotland, and Ireland since 8 March 1702, and so became Queen of Great Britain upon the Union of England and Scotland. Her total reign lasted for 12 years and 21 weeks.\n\n{{Nobility table header|arms=yes|extra column=Claim !! Ref.}}\n\n|-\n! class=noprint colspan=2 style=\"font-weight:normal\" | {{xref|Before the [[Acts of Union 1707]]|selfref=no}} {{arrow}}\n! class=noprint colspan=6 style=\"font-weight:normal\" | {{xref|See [[List of English monarchs]], [[List of Scottish monarchs]]}}\n|-\n| <big>[[Anne, Queen of Great Britain|'''Anne''']]</big><br />1 May 1707<br />{{ndash}}<br />1 August 1714<br />''({{age in years and days|1707|5|1|1714|8|1}})''\n| [[File:Dahl, Michael - Queen Anne - NPG 6187.jpg|100px]]\n| [[File:Royal Arms of Great Britain (1707-1714).svg|100px]]\n| 6 February 1665<br />[[St James's Palace]]<hr />Daughter of [[James II and VII]]<br/>and [[Anne Hyde]]\n| [[Prince George of Denmark]]<br />[[St James's Palace]]<br />28 July 1683<br />No surviving children\n| 1 August 1714<br />[[Kensington Palace]]<br />Age: {{ayd|1665|2|6|1714|8|1}}\n| Daughter of [[James II and VII]]<hr />[[Cognatic primogeniture]]{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}<hr />[[Bill of Rights 1689]]\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royal.uk/anne-r-1702-1714|title=Anne (r. 1702\u20131714)|website=royal.gov.uk|accessdate=16 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180125020033/https://www.royal.uk/anne-r-1702-1714|archive-date=25 January 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n|}\n\n==House of Hanover (1714\u20131901)==\n{{Main article|House of Hanover}}\nThe Hanoverian succession came about as a result of the [[Act of Settlement 1701]], passed by the [[Parliament of England]], which excluded \"[[Papist]]s\" (i.e. Roman Catholics) from the succession. In return for access to the [[English overseas possessions|English plantations in North America and the West Indies]], the Hanoverian succession and the Union were ratified by the [[Parliament of Scotland]] in 1707.\n\nAfter the death of Anne, with no living children, her second cousin, George Louis, was the closest heir to the throne who was not Catholic. George was the son of [[Sophia of Hanover]]\u2014granddaughter of [[James VI and I]] through his daughter [[Elizabeth Stuart, Queen of Bohemia|Elizabeth]].{{efn-lr|For a family tree showing King George I's relationship to Queen Anne, see {{Slink|George I of Great Britain|Family tree}}.}}  The Hanoverian kings of Great Britain retained their German titles, first as [[Elector of Hanover|electors of Hanover]]/[[Duchy of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg|dukes of Brunswick-L\u00fcneburg]] and later as [[King of Hanover|kings of Hanover]]; the two lands were ruled as separate states in personal union.  The Hanoverian lands were separated when [[Queen Victoria]] ascended the throne of Great Britain; as German succession law prevented women from inheriting the Hanoverian throne, her uncle [[Ernest Augustus, King of Hanover|Ernest Augustus]] inherited in her stead.\n\n{{Nobility table header|arms=yes|extra column=Claim !! Ref.}}\n\n|-\n| <big>[[George I of Great Britain|{{nowrap|'''George I'''}}]]</big><br />'''George Louis'''<br />1 August 1714{{efn|King George I was crowned on 20 October 1714.}}<br />{{ndash}}<br />11 June 1727<br />''({{ayd|1714|8|1|1727|6|11|duration=yes}})''\n| [[File:King George I by Sir Godfrey Kneller, Bt.jp